{"title_page": "Jogger's Park", "text_new": "{{short description|Public park in Mumbai, India}}\n[[File:Joggerspark.JPG|thumb|Jogger's Park, 2008]]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2017}}\n{{for|the Bollywood film|Joggers' Park (film)}}\n\n'''Jogger's Park''' is a seaside [[jogging]] track along with a park in [[Bandra]], [[Mumbai]]. It is situated at the southern end of the [[Carter Road Promenade|Carter Road]]. The park was opened to the public on 27 May 1990 and receives more than 2000 visitors on weekdays and double the number on Sundays.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/espnw/features/article/6851372/jogger-park-mumbai-inspires-runners|title=Joggers park in Mumbai inspires runners|work= [[ESPN.com]]|date= 13 August 2011| accessdate=10 October 2014}}</ref> Its jogging track is 400 metres long. It features a mud strip for running and two paved tracks for walking or jogging.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/mumbai/keep-on-running/article1-595385.aspx |title=Keep on running |work=[[Hindustan Times]] |date=3 September 2010 |accessdate=10 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018082448/http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/mumbai/keep-on-running/article1-595385.aspx |archivedate=18 October 2014 }}</ref>\n\nDevelopment of the park is credited to the city's veteran hockey coach and former corporator, Oliver Andrade.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.mid-day.com/news/2002/oct/35063.htm|title=Oliver is not feeling hardy|work= [[Mid-day]]|date= 30 October 2002| accessdate=10 October 2014}}</ref> Andrade's effort to rope in films star [[Dilip Kumar]] and [[Sunil Dutt]], transformed the site from a dumping ground into a jogging track. The movie star's fund raising efforts led to financial assistance from the Rahejas, the Lokhandwalas and the Rizvi builders at a cost of \u20b94 crore.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://expressindia.indianexpress.com/ie/daily/19990608/ige08086.html |title=It's a thankless job, say private trusts |work=[[The Indian Express]] |date=8 June 1999 |accessdate=10 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018160008/http://expressindia.indianexpress.com/ie/daily/19990608/ige08086.html |archivedate=18 October 2014 }}</ref> In his memory, a plaque at the entrance of the park reads \"From Sir with Love\". [[Mumbai]]'s first [[laughter club]] was launched at Joggers Park.{{citation needed|date=October 2014}}\n\n==History==\nJoggers Park was conceived by Oliver Andrade of Bandra, Bombay. Oliver Andrade was fondly called \"Sir\" as he was responsible for coaching Hockey and Football to thousands of students of [[St. Theresa's Boys High School]], St. Stanislaus High School and Sacred Heart High School. Andrade wanted to develop a park for the citizens on a plot of land facing the sea in Bandra, which had turned into a dump yard over the years. He approached various eminent citizens of Mumbai, notably, [[Sunil Dutt]], [[Dilip Kumar]] and pursued with various local and state authorities to get his plan sanctioned. \nAs soon as he received a go-ahead from the authorities, Andrade raised money for the park by convincing the leading three construction companies who were located in Bandra. As a result of his effort, Lokhandwala Builders agreed to develop the cost ''[[pro bono]]''. The external wall facing the sea was developed ''pro bono'' by Raheja Builders and Rizvi Builders. The founders of all these companies were former students of Andrade and they were happy to invest money in a cause that was for the citizens of Bombay.\n\n==Park Management==\nThe Lokhandwala family agreed to manage the day-to-day operations and maintenance of the park. The family's trust Bombay Suburban Civic Trust was the official caretaker of the park, having obtained the rights to manage the park from the Bombay Municipal Corporation. art\n\nThe MCGM took back the control of the park from the Bombay Suburban Civic Trust on 31 January 2017.\n\n==Entry Fee==\nThe Park does not charge an entry fee since 1 February 2007. When the park was inaugurated, the entry fee was \u20b91 which was increased to \u20b92 a decade later. The original timings of the park (until 31 January 2017) was 5:30 AM to 9:30AM and 3:30PM to 9:00PM. However after the takeover by the MCGM, the cooling time in the afternoon has been withdrawn and the park is open from 5:00AM to 9:00PM.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report-bandra-locals-join-hands-with-bmc-to-save-joggers-park-2341930|title=Bandra locals join hands with BMC to 'save' Joggers Park \u2013 Latest News & Updates at Daily News & Analysis|date=4 March 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Save Joggers Park==\nCitizens and Joggers got together on 2 Feb 2017 under the banner of a spontaneous movement to save the park. This movement evolved into the Save Joggers Park Group which is pursuing the agenda of the upkeep of the park.\nThe Save Joggers Park group has roped in thousands of patrons and users of the Joggers park. They have also initiated dialogues with elected representatives, Municipal authorities and officials of the Garden department of MCGM.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Maharashtra}}\n\n[[Category:Parks in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Bandra]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Public park in Mumbai, India}}\n[[File:Joggerspark.JPG|thumb|Jogger's Park, 2008]]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2017}}\n{{for|the Bollywood film|Joggers' Park (film)}}\n\n'''Jogger's Park''' is a seaside [[jogging]] track along with a park in [[Bandra]], [[Mumbai]]. It is situated next to the [[Otters Club]], off [[Carter Road Promenade|Carter Road]]. The park was opened to the public on 27 May 1990 and receives more than 2000 visitors on weekdays and double the number on Sundays.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/espnw/features/article/6851372/jogger-park-mumbai-inspires-runners|title=Joggers park in Mumbai inspires runners|work= [[ESPN.com]]|date= 13 August 2011| accessdate=10 October 2014}}</ref> Its jogging track is 400 metres long. It features a mud strip for running and two paved tracks for walking or jogging.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/mumbai/keep-on-running/article1-595385.aspx |title=Keep on running |work=[[Hindustan Times]] |date=3 September 2010 |accessdate=10 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018082448/http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/mumbai/keep-on-running/article1-595385.aspx |archivedate=18 October 2014 }}</ref>\n\nDevelopment of the park is credited to the city's veteran hockey coach and former corporator, Oliver Andrade.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.mid-day.com/news/2002/oct/35063.htm|title=Oliver is not feeling hardy|work= [[Mid-day]]|date= 30 October 2002| accessdate=10 October 2014}}</ref> Andrade transformed the site from a dumping ground into a jogging track with financial assistance from the Rahejas, the Lokhandwalas and the Rizvi builders at a cost of \u20b94 crore.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://expressindia.indianexpress.com/ie/daily/19990608/ige08086.html |title=It's a thankless job, say private trusts |work=[[The Indian Express]] |date=8 June 1999 |accessdate=10 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018160008/http://expressindia.indianexpress.com/ie/daily/19990608/ige08086.html |archivedate=18 October 2014 }}</ref> In his memory, a plaque at the entrance of the park reads \"From Sir with Love\". [[Mumbai]]'s first [[laughter club]] was launched at Joggers Park.{{citation needed|date=October 2014}}\n\n==History==\nJoggers Park was conceived by Oliver Andrade of Bandra, Bombay. Oliver Andrade was fondly called \"Sir\" as he was responsible for coaching Hockey and Football to thousands of students of [[St. Theresa's Boys High School]], St. Stanislaus High School and Sacred Heart High School. Andrade wanted to develop a park for the citizens on a plot of land facing the sea in Bandra, which had turned into a dump yard over the years. He approached various eminent citizens of Mumbai, notably, [[Sunil Dutt]], [[Dilip Kumar]] and pursued with various local and state authorities to get his plan sanctioned. \nAs soon as he received a go-ahead from the authorities, Andrade raised money for the park by convincing the leading three construction companies who were located in Bandra. As a result of his effort, Lokhandwala Builders agreed to develop the cost ''[[pro bono]]''. The external wall facing the sea was developed ''pro bono'' by Raheja Builders and Rizvi Builders. The founders of all these companies were former students of Andrade and they were happy to invest money in a cause that was for the citizens of Bombay.\n\n==Park Management==\nThe Lokhandwala family agreed to manage the day-to-day operations and maintenance of the park. The family's trust Bombay Suburban Civic Trust was the official caretaker of the park, having obtained the rights to manage the park from the Bombay Municipal Corporation. art\n\nThe MCGM took back the control of the park from the Bombay Suburban Civic Trust on 31 January 2017.\n\n==Entry Fee==\nThe Park does not charge an entry fee since 1 February 2007. When the park was inaugurated, the entry fee was \u20b91 which was increased to \u20b92 a decade later. The original timings of the park (until 31 January 2017) was 5:30 AM to 9:30AM and 3:30PM to 9:00PM. However after the takeover by the MCGM, the cooling time in the afternoon has been withdrawn and the park is open from 5:00AM to 9:00PM.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report-bandra-locals-join-hands-with-bmc-to-save-joggers-park-2341930|title=Bandra locals join hands with BMC to 'save' Joggers Park \u2013 Latest News & Updates at Daily News & Analysis|date=4 March 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Save Joggers Park==\nCitizens and Joggers got together on 2 Feb 2017 under the banner of a spontaneous movement to save the park. This movement evolved into the Save Joggers Park Group which is pursuing the agenda of the upkeep of the park.\nThe Save Joggers Park group has roped in thousands of patrons and users of the Joggers park. They have also initiated dialogues with elected representatives, Municipal authorities and officials of the Garden department of MCGM.\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Maharashtra}}\n\n[[Category:Parks in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Bandra]]\n", "name_user": "Cokestunt", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jogger%27s_Park"}
{"title_page": "Jim Rubens", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n|name         = Jim Rubens\n|state_senate = New Hampshire\n|district    = 5th\n|term_start  = January 1994\n|term_end    = January 1998\n|predecessor = [[Ralph D. Hough]]\n|successor   = [[Clifton Below]]\n|birth_date  = \n|birth_place = [[Brooklyn|New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|alma_mater  = [[Dartmouth College]]\n|website     = [http://www.jimrubens.com Official website]\n}}\n'''Jim Rubens''' is an American politician from the state of [[New Hampshire]]. A member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], Rubens served in the [[New Hampshire Senate]] for two terms.\n\n==Biography==\nRubens was born in [[Brooklyn]]. He attended [[Dartmouth College]]. He worked as a developer and investor.<ref name=bio/>\n\nIdentifying himself as a [[fiscal conservative]], Rubens formed a new [[political party]] in 1993, called the New Majority, an offshoot of the [[Independence Party of New York]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=FV8gAAAAIBAJ&sjid=hmUFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5118,1168102&dq=jim-rubens&hl=en|title=Arnssen, Rauh take part in party formation|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=Sun Journal|page=13|date=August 6, 1993|accessdate=October 11, 2013}}</ref> Rubens ran for the [[New Hampshire Senate]] in 1994, challenging [[Ralph Hough]] in the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] [[primary election]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yGIgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=52UFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3483,3928190&dq=jim-rubens&hl=en|title=Candidate wants education reform|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=Sun Journal|page=11|date=March 18, 1994|accessdate=October 11, 2013}}</ref> Rubens defeated Hough, and won in the general election. In 1995 he was sworn in.<ref name=bio>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=NTGB&p_theme=ntgb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=106E85AFCAEF768C&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=Jim Rubens |newspaper=Nashua Telegraph.com |page=13 |date=September 4, 1998 |accessdate=October 11, 2013}} {{subscription required|date=October 2013}}</ref> Rubens was reelected in 1996. Rather than run for reelection to the New Hampshire Senate in 1998, he ran for [[Governor of New Hampshire]] in the [[New Hampshire gubernatorial election, 1998|1998 election]], but lost. Rubens ran again for the state Senate in 2000,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=NTGB&p_theme=ntgb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=1070DF93A9FF16BA&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=Archive Search - NashuaTelegraph.com|website=nl.newsbank.com|accessdate=May 7, 2017}}</ref> but lost.\n\nRubens recently served as the chairman of the [[Granite State Coalition Against Expanded Gambling]]. He stepped down from this position when he became a candidate for the [[United States Senate]], seeking the Republican nomination in the [[United States Senate election in New Hampshire, 2014|2014 election]].<ref name=concord>{{cite web|url=http://www.concordmonitor.com/home/8491803-95/gops-jim-rubens-announces-run-for-us-senate-slams-incumbent-democrat-jeanne-shaheen |title=GOP\u2019s Jim Rubens announces run for U.S. Senate, slams incumbent Democrat Jeanne Shaheen |publisher=Concord Monitor |accessdate=October 11, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130923102044/http://www.concordmonitor.com/home/8491803-95/gops-jim-rubens-announces-run-for-us-senate-slams-incumbent-democrat-jeanne-shaheen |archivedate=September 23, 2013 }}</ref> He had the support of the [[Mayday PAC]] for the race.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mayday.us/rubens/ |title=Jim Rubens |publisher=Mayday PAC |accessdate=August 21, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140827180149/https://mayday.us/rubens/ |archivedate=August 27, 2014 }}</ref> Rubens lost the primary election to [[Scott Brown (politician)|Scott Brown]].\n\nRubens lost to incumbent Senator [[Kelly Ayotte]] in the [[United States Senate election in New Hampshire, 2016|2016 election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nh1.com/news/steinhauser-rubens-tells-nh1-news-he-s-conservative-alternative-to-ayotte-says-senate-should-absolutely-vote-on-potential-obama-scotus-nominee/|title=Steinhauser: Rubens tells NH1 News he's conservative alternative to Ayotte, says Senate should 'absolutely' vote on potential Obama SCOTUS nominee - NH1|website=NH1|accessdate=May 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\nRubens has anti-feminist views. In 2013, Rubens claims that women in the workplace are partially to blame for mass shootings. \u201cThe collaborative, flexible, amorphously-hierarchical American economy is shutting out ordinary men who were once the nation\u2019s breadwinners in living-wage labor and manufacturing jobs,\u201d Rubens wrote. \u201cBecause status success is more vital to the male psychology, males are falling over the edge in increasing numbers.\u201d\n\nHe continues by adding, \u201cThe collapsing number of male jobs in the increasingly female-centric economy just adds to the already harsher impact of OverSuccess on males,\u201d in which he refers to his 2008 book where he explores America's obsession with wealth, fame, power and perfection.<ref>https://www.guns.com/news/2013/09/21/u-s-senate-candidate-claims-women-workplace-partially-responsible-mass-shootings.</ref>\n\n==Personal==\nRubens is from [[Hanover, New Hampshire]].<ref name=concord/> He has a wife and a son.<ref name=bio/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.jimrubens.com/ Official campaign site]\n* {{CongLinks | congbio= | votesmart= | fec=C00550780 | congress= }}<!--\nLinks formerly displayed 