{"title_page": "Silvano Ciampi", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Silvano Ciampi\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1932|2|22|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| currentteam    = \n| discipline     = \n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      = \n| amateuryears1  = \n| amateurteam1   = \n| proyears1      = \n| proteam1       = \n| majorwins      = \n| show-medals    = yes\n| medaltemplates = \n}}\n'''Silvano Ciampi''' (born 22 February 1932) is an Italian [[bicycle racing|racing cyclist]].<ref name=\"CA\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cyclingarchives.com/coureurfiche.php?coureurid=1354 |title=Silvano Ciampi |accessdate=12 May 2017 |work=Cycling Archives}}</ref> He won stage 6 of the [[1958 Giro d'Italia]].<ref name=\"Giro\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cyclingarchives.com/ritfiche.php?ritid=150180 |title=Giro d'Italia 1958 |accessdate=12 May 2017 |work=Cycling Archives}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Cycling Archives|1354}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ciampi, Silvano}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Italian Giro d'Italia stage winners]]\n[[Category:Giro d'Italia cyclists]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n{{Italy-cycling-bio-1930s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Italian cyclist}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Silvano Ciampi\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1932|2|22|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| currentteam    = \n| discipline     = \n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      = \n| amateuryears1  = \n| amateurteam1   = \n| proyears1      = \n| proteam1       = \n| majorwins      = \n| show-medals    = yes\n| medaltemplates = \n}}\n'''Silvano Ciampi''' (born 22 February 1932) is an Italian [[bicycle racing|racing cyclist]].<ref name=\"CA\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cyclingarchives.com/coureurfiche.php?coureurid=1354 |title=Silvano Ciampi |accessdate=12 May 2017 |work=Cycling Archives}}</ref> He won stage 6 of the [[1958 Giro d'Italia]].<ref name=\"Giro\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cyclingarchives.com/ritfiche.php?ritid=150180 |title=Giro d'Italia 1958 |accessdate=12 May 2017 |work=Cycling Archives}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Cycling Archives|1354}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ciampi, Silvano}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Italian Giro d'Italia stage winners]]\n[[Category:Giro d'Italia cyclists]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n{{Italy-cycling-bio-1930s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Silvano_Ciampi"}
{"title_page": "Henry B. Quinby", "text_new": "{{Infobox Governor\n|name        = Henry Brewer Quinby\n|image       = Henry Brewer Quinby.png \n| caption =\n|order       = 52nd \n|office      = Governor of New Hampshire\n|term_start  = January 7, 1909\t\n|term_end    =  January 5, 1911\n|predecessor =  [[Charles M. Floyd]]\n|successor   =  [[Robert P. Bass]]\n| order2 = Member of the [[Executive Council of New Hampshire]]\n| term_start2 =1891\n| term_end2 = 1892\n| predecessor2 = \n| successor2 = \n| order3 = Member of the [[New Hampshire Senate]]\n| term_start3 =1889\n| term_end3 = 1890\n| predecessor3 = \n| successor3 =  \n| order4 = Member of the [[New Hampshire House of Representatives]]\n| term_start4 =1887\n| term_end4 = 1888\n| predecessor4 = \n| successor4 =  \n| nationality = American\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1846|06|10}}\n| birth_place = {{nowrap|[[Biddeford, Maine|Biddeford]], [[Maine]], U.S.}}\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1924|02|8|1846|06|10|mf=yes}}\n| death_place = {{nowrap|[[New York City|New York]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.}}\n|resting_place=\n|party       =  [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse      = Octavia M. Cole\n|children=Henry Cole Quinby<br>Candace Ellen Quinby\n|alma_mater =  [[Bowdoin College]], A.B., 1869<br>[[Bowdoin College]], A.M., 1872<br>[[George Washington University Medical School|National Medical College]], 1880\n|profession  = Physician<br>Businessman<br>Politician\n|religion    = [[Unitarianism|Unitarian]]\n}}\n'''Henry Brewer Quinby''' (June 10, 1846&nbsp;\u2013 February 8, 1924) was an [[United States|American]] physician, businessman, and [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] politician in the [[U.S. state]] of [[New Hampshire]]. He was the [[Governor of New Hampshire|52nd Governor of New Hampshire]] and served in the [[New Hampshire House of Representatives]] and the [[New Hampshire Senate]].\n\n==Early life==\nQuinby was born in [[Biddeford, Maine]] to Thomas and Jane E. (Brewer) Quinby. He earned a bachelor's degree from [[Bowdoin College]] in 1869 and a [[Master's degree|A.M. degree]] from Bowdoin in 1872. In 1880, he graduated from the [[George Washington University Medical School|National Medical College]] in Washington, D.C.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.library.unh.edu/special/index.php/henry-quinby|title= Guide to the Henry Brewer Quinby (1846-1925) and Henry Cole Quinby (1872-1922) Papers, 1863-1927|publisher= University of New Hampshire Library|accessdate= December 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nHe served in the New Hampshire House of Representatives from 1887-1888 and in the New Hampshire Senate from 1889\u20131890. He was on the [[New Hampshire]] [[Executive Council of New Hampshire|Executive Council]] in 1891 and 1892.<ref>{{cite book|last=|title=Granite Monthly: A New Hampshire Magazine, Volumes 43-44|year=1911|page=353|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mGESAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA1-PA353&dq=Henry+B.+Quinby+Executive+Council+of+New+Hampshire&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ZQ2tUu2QOoTF2AX2_4HACQ&ved=0CDQQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=Henry%20B.%20Quinby%20Executive%20Council%20of%20New%20Hampshire&f=false}}</ref> In 1893, he was a delegate to the Republican National Convention. Quinby was chairman of the 1896 State Republican Convention.\n\nHe was elected as a Republican candidate to the office of governor in 1908.<ref>{{cite book|last=Metcalf|first=Henry Harrison  and Abbott, Frances Matilda|title=One Thousand New Hampshire Notables: Brief Biographical Sketches of New Hampshire Men and Women, Native Or Resident, Prominent in Public, Professional, Business, Educational, Fraternal Or Benevolent Work|year=1919|publisher=Rumford Printing Company|page=[https://archive.org/details/onethousandnewh00metcgoog/page/n315 301]|url=https://archive.org/details/onethousandnewh00metcgoog|quote=henry brewer quinby governor nh.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=New England Magazine Company|title=The New England Magazine, Volume 39|year=1909|publisher=New England Magazine Company|page=164|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TeI5AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA163&lpg=PA163&dq=henry+brewer+quinby+governor+nh&source=bl&ots=zXGgUaTm4D&sig=4ZjCSUIfnbxvI_Imn-IPxDOHqyE&hl=en&sa=X&ei=zBGtUv71CsqqsAT85ICICg&ved=0CEkQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=henry%20brewer%20quinby%20governor%20nh&f=false}}</ref>  After leaving office, he retired from politics.\n\nHe died in 1924 in [[New York City]].\n\n==Personal life==\nOn June 22, 1870, Quinby married Octavia M. Cole and they had two children,  Henry Cole Quinby and Candace Ellen Quinby.<ref>{{cite book|last=Hammon|first=Otis Grant|title=The Granite Monthly: A Magazine of Literature, History and State Progress, Volume 44|year=1912|publisher=J.N. McClintock|page=354|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3hgXAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA75&lpg=PA75&dq=Henry+B.+Quinby+married+Octavia+M.+Cole&source=bl&ots=aSMhYewkKx&sig=qD0c6m1Uqfu45GgeGdE7zgH0Dao&hl=en&sa=X&ei=0gqtUt63JabI2AXCvIC4CQ&ved=0CDsQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=Henry%20B.%20Quinby%20married%20Octavia%20M.%20Cole&f=false}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n <!-- for current and future use if material is uploaded -->\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050305192036/http://www.state.nh.us/nhdhr/glikeness/quinhenr.html Quinby at New Hampshire's Division of Historic Resources]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070930041500/http://www.nga.org/portal/site/nga/menuitem.29fab9fb4add37305ddcbeeb501010a0/?vgnextoid=b6f2f84c3266a010VgnVCM1000001a01010aRCRD&vgnextchannel=e449a0ca9e3f1010VgnVCM1000001a01010aRCRD New Hampshire Governor Henry Brewer Quinby]\n* [http://www.library.unh.edu/special/index.php/henry-quinby University of New Hampshire Library]\n* [http://www.nga.org/cms/home/governors/past-governors-bios/page_new_hampshire/col2-content/main-content-list/title_quinby_henry.html National Governors Association]\n\n<br/><!--this break is to put visual space between the last information and the following template if needed-->\t\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box |title=[[List of Governors of New Hampshire|Governor of New Hampshire]] | before=[[Charles M. Floyd]] | after=[[Robert P. Bass]] | years=1909\u20131911}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Governors of New Hampshire}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Quinby, Henry B.}}\n[[Category:1846 births]]\n[[Category:1924 deaths]]\n[[Category:Bowdoin College alumni]]\n[[Category:Governors of New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:American Unitarians]]\n[[Category:People from Biddeford, Maine]]\n[[Category:People from Laconia, New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Members of the New Hampshire House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:New Hampshire state senators]]\n[[Category:New Hampshire Republicans]]\n[[Category:Republican Party state governors of the United States]]\n\n\n{{NewHampshire-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Governor\n|name        = Henry Brewer Quinby\n|image       = Henry Brewer Quinby.png \n| caption =\n|order       = 52nd \n|office      = Governor of New Hampshire\n|term_start  = January 7, 1909\t\n|term_end    =  January 5, 1911\n|predecessor =  [[Charles M. Floyd]]\n|successor   =  [[Robert P. Bass]]\n| order2 = Member of the [[Executive Council of New Hampshire]]\n| term_start2 =1891\n| term_end2 = 1892\n| predecessor2 = \n| successor2 = \n| order3 = Member of the [[New Hampshire Senate]]\n| term_start3 =1889\n| term_end3 = 1890\n| predecessor3 = \n| successor3 =  \n| order4 = Member of the [[New Hampshire House of Representatives]]\n| term_start4 =1887\n| term_end4 = 1888\n| predecessor4 = \n| successor4 =  \n| nationality = American\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1846|06|10}}\n| birth_place = {{nowrap|[[Biddeford, Maine|Biddeford]], [[Maine]], U.S.}}\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1924|02|8|1846|06|10|mf=yes}}\n| death_place = {{nowrap|[[New York City|New York]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.}}\n|resting_place=\n|party       =  [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse      = Octavia M. Cole\n|children=Henry Cole Quinby<br>Candace Ellen Quinby\n|alma_mater =  [[Bowdoin College]], A.B., 1869<br>[[Bowdoin College]], A.M., 1872<br>[[George Washington University Medical School|National Medical College]], 1880\n|profession  = Physician<br>Businessman<br>Politician\n|religion    = [[Unitarianism|Unitarian]]\n}}\n'''Henry Brewer Quinby''' (June 10, 1846&nbsp;\u2013 February 8, 1924) was an [[United States|American]] physician, businessman, and [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] politician in the [[U.S. state]] of [[New Hampshire]]. He was the [[Governor of New Hampshire|52nd Governor of New Hampshire]] and served in the [[New Hampshire House of Representatives]] and the [[New Hampshire Senate]].\n\n==Early life==\nQuinby was born in [[Biddeford, Maine]] to Thomas and Jane E. (Brewer) Quinby. He earned a bachelor's degree from [[Bowdoin College]] in 1869 and a [[Master's degree|A.M. degree]] from Bowdoin in 1872. In 1880, he graduated from the [[George Washington University Medical School|National Medical College]] in Washington, D.C.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.library.unh.edu/special/index.php/henry-quinby|title= Guide to the Henry Brewer Quinby (1846-1925) and Henry Cole Quinby (1872-1922) Papers, 1863-1927|publisher= University of New Hampshire Library|accessdate= December 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nHe served in the New Hampshire House of Representatives from 1887-1888 and in the New Hampshire Senate from 1889-1890. He was on the [[New Hampshire]] [[Executive Council of New Hampshire|Executive Council]] in 1891 and 1892.<ref>{{cite book|last=|title=Granite Monthly: A New Hampshire Magazine, Volumes 43-44|year=1911|page=353|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mGESAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA1-PA353&dq=Henry+B.+Quinby+Executive+Council+of+New+Hampshire&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ZQ2tUu2QOoTF2AX2_4HACQ&ved=0CDQQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=Henry%20B.%20Quinby%20Executive%20Council%20of%20New%20Hampshire&f=false}}</ref> In 1893, he was a delegate to the Republican National Convention. Quinby was chairman of the 1896 State Republican Convention.\n\nHe was elected as a Republican candidate to the office of governor in 1908.<ref>{{cite book|last=Metcalf|first=Henry Harrison  and Abbott, Frances Matilda|title=One Thousand New Hampshire Notables: Brief Biographical Sketches of New Hampshire Men and Women, Native Or Resident, Prominent in Public, Professional, Business, Educational, Fraternal Or Benevolent Work|year=1919|publisher=Rumford Printing Company|page=[https://archive.org/details/onethousandnewh00metcgoog/page/n315 301]|url=https://archive.org/details/onethousandnewh00metcgoog|quote=henry brewer quinby governor nh.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=New England Magazine Company|title=The New England Magazine, Volume 39|year=1909|publisher=New England Magazine Company|page=164|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TeI5AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA163&lpg=PA163&dq=henry+brewer+quinby+governor+nh&source=bl&ots=zXGgUaTm4D&sig=4ZjCSUIfnbxvI_Imn-IPxDOHqyE&hl=en&sa=X&ei=zBGtUv71CsqqsAT85ICICg&ved=0CEkQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=henry%20brewer%20quinby%20governor%20nh&f=false}}</ref>  After leaving office, he retired from politics.\n\nHe died in 1924 in [[New York City]].\n\n==Personal life==\nOn June 22, 1870, Quinby married Octavia M. Cole and they had two children,  Henry Cole Quinby and Candace Ellen Quinby.<ref>{{cite book|last=Hammon|first=Otis Grant|title=The Granite Monthly: A Magazine of Literature, History and State Progress, Volume 44|year=1912|publisher=J.N. McClintock|page=354|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3hgXAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA75&lpg=PA75&dq=Henry+B.+Quinby+married+Octavia+M.+Cole&source=bl&ots=aSMhYewkKx&sig=qD0c6m1Uqfu45GgeGdE7zgH0Dao&hl=en&sa=X&ei=0gqtUt63JabI2AXCvIC4CQ&ved=0CDsQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=Henry%20B.%20Quinby%20married%20Octavia%20M.%20Cole&f=false}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n <!-- for current and future use if material is uploaded -->\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050305192036/http://www.state.nh.us/nhdhr/glikeness/quinhenr.html Quinby at New Hampshire's Division of Historic Resources]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070930041500/http://www.nga.org/portal/site/nga/menuitem.29fab9fb4add37305ddcbeeb501010a0/?vgnextoid=b6f2f84c3266a010VgnVCM1000001a01010aRCRD&vgnextchannel=e449a0ca9e3f1010VgnVCM1000001a01010aRCRD New Hampshire Governor Henry Brewer Quinby]\n* [http://www.library.unh.edu/special/index.php/henry-quinby University of New Hampshire Library]\n* [http://www.nga.org/cms/home/governors/past-governors-bios/page_new_hampshire/col2-content/main-content-list/title_quinby_henry.html National Governors Association]\n\n<br/><!--this break is to put visual space between the last information and the following template if needed-->\t\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box |title=[[List of Governors of New Hampshire|Governor of New Hampshire]] | before=[[Charles M. Floyd]] | after=[[Robert P. Bass]] | years=1909\u20131911}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Governors of New Hampshire}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Quinby, Henry B.}}\n[[Category:1846 births]]\n[[Category:1924 deaths]]\n[[Category:Bowdoin College alumni]]\n[[Category:Governors of New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:American Unitarians]]\n[[Category:People from Biddeford, Maine]]\n[[Category:People from Laconia, New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Members of the New Hampshire House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:New Hampshire state senators]]\n[[Category:New Hampshire Republicans]]\n[[Category:Republican Party state governors of the United States]]\n\n\n{{NewHampshire-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePolitical career:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1889-1890 \u2192 1889\u20131890", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_B._Quinby"}
{"title_page": "Take Me There (Rascal Flatts song)", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=September 2008}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Take Me There\n| cover      = Rascal Flatts - Take Me There cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Rascal Flatts]]\n| album      = [[Still Feels Good]]\n| released   = July 9, 2007\n| format     = [[CD single]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[country music|Country]]\n| length     = 4:26\n| label      = [[Lyric Street Records|Lyric Street]]\n| writer     = [[Kenny Chesney]], [[Wendell Mobley]], [[Neil Thrasher]]\n| producer   = [[Dann Huff]], Rascal Flatts\n| prev_title = [[Stand (Rascal Flatts song)|Stand]]\n| prev_year  = 2007\n| next_title = [[Winner at a Losing Game]]\n| next_year  = 2007\n}}\n\"'''Take Me There'''\" is a song recorded by American [[country music]] group [[Rascal Flatts]].  It was released in July 2007 as the first single from their album ''[[Still Feels Good]]''.  The song became their eighth number-one hit on the Hot Country Songs Chart the week of September 16, 2007. The song was co-written by [[Kenny Chesney]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cmt.com/artists/news/1563929/20070702/rascal_flatts.jhtml |title=Rascal Flatts' New Single Co-Written by Kenny Chesney |accessdate=2008-09-07 |work=cmt.com}}</ref> along with [[Neil Thrasher]] (who also co-wrote Rascal Flatts' 2003 single \"[[I Melt]]\") and [[Wendell Mobley]].\n\n==Charts==\nFor the week of September 22, 2007, the song became the group's third consecutive number one hit.\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (2007)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardcountrysongs|1|artist=Rascal Flatts|artistid=395934}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|19|artist=Rascal Flatts|artistid=395934}}\n|-\n|US ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Pop 100]]\n|align=\"center\"|33\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardcanadianhot100|49|artist=Rascal Flatts|artistid=395934}}\n|}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n