{"title_page": "Jared Perkins", "text_new": "{{Infobox Congressman\n| name                =Jared Perkins  \n| image               = \n| state               =[[New Hampshire]]\n| district            =[[New Hampshire's 3rd congressional district|3rd]]\n| term_start          =March 4, 1851\n| term_end            =March 3, 1853 \n| preceded            =[[George W. Morrison]] \n| succeeded           = [[Harry Hibbard]]\n| office2            = Member of the<br>[[New Hampshire Executive Council]]  \n| term_start2          =1846 \n| term_end2            = 1848 \n| preceded2            = \n| succeeded2           =\n| office3            = Member of the<br>[[New Hampshire House of Representatives]]   \n| term_start3          =1850\n| term_end3            =1850\n| preceded3            = \n| succeeded3           =\n| birth_date          =January 5, 1793  \n| birth_place         =[[Unity, New Hampshire]] \n| death_date          ={{Death date and age|1854|10|15|1793|01|05|mf=yes}}\n| death_place         =[[Nashua, New Hampshire]] \n|restingplace=  \n| nationality         =\n| party               = [[Whig Party (United States)|Whig]]\n| otherparty          =\n| spouse              =\n| relations           =\n| children            =  \n| residence           =\n| alma_mater          =  \n| occupation          = \n| profession          =\n| religion            =\n| signature           =\n| website             =\n| footnotes           =\n}}\n'''Jared Perkins''' (January 5, 1793 \u2013 October 15, 1854) was a [[United States Representative]] from [[New Hampshire]].  He was born in [[Unity, New Hampshire]] and attended the common schools of Unity and [[Claremont, New Hampshire|Claremont]]. He studied [[theology]] and was ordained as a minister in 1824, serving for thirty years.\n\nPerkins served on the [[New Hampshire Executive Council]] 1846\u20131848. He also served in the [[New Hampshire House of Representatives]] in 1850. He was elected as a [[Whig Party (United States)|Whig]] to the [[Thirty-second Congress]] (March 4, 1851 \u2013 March 3, 1853) but was an unsuccessful candidate for reelection in 1852 to the [[Thirty-third Congress]]. After leaving Congress, he was nominated for [[Governor of New Hampshire]] in 1854 but died before the election. In addition, he was also appointed justice of the peace in 1854 and served until his death in [[Nashua, New Hampshire|Nashua]] in 1854. He was buried in West Unity Cemetery, Unity, New Hampshire.\n\n==References==\n\n==Sources==\n{{CongBio|P000235}}\n*{{Findagrave|6964484}}\n*[http://politicalgraveyard.com/bio/perkins.html Jared Perkins] at The Political Graveyard\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{succession box|\n before=[[George W. Morrison]]|\n  title=[[U.S. Congressional Delegations from New Hampshire|U.S. Representative for the 3rd District of New Hampshire]]|\n  years=March 4, 1851 \u2013 March 3, 1853|\n  after=[[Harry Hibbard]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Perkins, Jared}}\n[[Category:1793 births]]\n[[Category:1854 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Unity, New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:New Hampshire Whigs]]\n[[Category:Members of the New Hampshire Executive Council]]\n[[Category:Members of the New Hampshire House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Whig Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n\n\n{{NewHampshire-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Congressman\n| name                =Jared Perkins  \n| image               = \n| state               =[[New Hampshire]]\n| district            =[[New Hampshire's 3rd congressional district|3rd]]\n| term_start          =March 4, 1851\n| term_end            =March 3, 1853 \n| preceded            =[[George W. Morrison]] \n| succeeded           = [[Harry Hibbard]]\n| office2            = Member of the<br>[[New Hampshire Executive Council]]  \n| term_start2          =1846 \n| term_end2            = 1848 \n| preceded2            = \n| succeeded2           =\n| office3            = Member of the<br>[[New Hampshire House of Representatives]]   \n| term_start3          =1850\n| term_end3            =1850\n| preceded3            = \n| succeeded3           =\n| birth_date          =January 5, 1793  \n| birth_place         =[[Unity, New Hampshire]] \n| death_date          ={{Death date and age|1854|10|15|1793|01|05|mf=yes}}\n| death_place         =[[Nashua, New Hampshire]] \n|restingplace=  \n| nationality         =\n| party               = [[Whig Party (United States)|Whig]]\n| otherparty          =\n| spouse              =\n| relations           =\n| children            =  \n| residence           =\n| alma_mater          =  \n| occupation          = \n| profession          =\n| religion            =\n| signature           =\n| website             =\n| footnotes           =\n}}\n'''Jared Perkins''' (January 5, 1793 \u2013 October 15, 1854) was a [[United States Representative]] from [[New Hampshire]].  He was born in [[Unity, New Hampshire]] and attended the common schools of Unity and [[Claremont, New Hampshire|Claremont]]. He studied [[theology]] and was ordained as a minister in 1824, serving for thirty years.\n\nPerkins served on the [[New Hampshire Executive Council]] 1846-1848. He also served in the [[New Hampshire House of Representatives]] in 1850. He was elected as a [[Whig Party (United States)|Whig]] to the [[Thirty-second Congress]] (March 4, 1851 \u2013 March 3, 1853) but was an unsuccessful candidate for reelection in 1852 to the [[Thirty-third Congress]]. After leaving Congress, he was nominated for [[Governor of New Hampshire]] in 1854 but died before the election. In addition, he was also appointed justice of the peace in 1854 and served until his death in [[Nashua, New Hampshire|Nashua]] in 1854. He was buried in West Unity Cemetery, Unity, New Hampshire.\n\n==References==\n\n==Sources==\n{{CongBio|P000235}}\n*{{Findagrave|6964484}}\n*[http://politicalgraveyard.com/bio/perkins.html Jared Perkins] at The Political Graveyard\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{succession box|\n before=[[George W. Morrison]]|\n  title=[[U.S. Congressional Delegations from New Hampshire|U.S. Representative for the 3rd District of New Hampshire]]|\n  years=March 4, 1851 \u2013 March 3, 1853|\n  after=[[Harry Hibbard]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Perkins, Jared}}\n[[Category:1793 births]]\n[[Category:1854 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Unity, New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:New Hampshire Whigs]]\n[[Category:Members of the New Hampshire Executive Council]]\n[[Category:Members of the New Hampshire House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Whig Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n\n\n{{NewHampshire-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1846-1848 \u2192 1846\u20131848", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jared_Perkins"}
{"title_page": "Paul Bardacke", "text_new": "{{Blacklisted-links|1=\n*http://www.lawyers.com/New-Mexico/Albuquerque/Paul-Bardacke-1134905-a.html\n*:''Triggered by <code>\\blawyers\\.com\\b</code> on the local blacklist''|bot=Cyberbot II|invisible=false}}\n{{BLP sources|date=December 2010}}\n'''Paul Gregory Bardacke''' (born December 16, 1944)<ref>[http://www.google.com/search?sourceid=chrome&ie=UTF-8&q=new+hampshire+birth+index+online#sclient=psy&hl=en&tbs=bks:1&q=General+corporate.+Home:+2223+E+Day+Island+Blvd+W+Tacoma+WA+98466-+1816+Office%3A+4303+N+Ruston+Way+Tacoma+WA+98402-5313+BARDACKE%2C+PAUL+GREGORY%2C+lawyer%2C+former+attorney+general%3B+b.+Oakland.+Calif.%2C+Dec.+16.+1944&aq=f&aqi=&aql=&oq=&psj=1&fp=cc7216a82c53364]</ref>     is the former [[Attorney General of New Mexico]], having served from 1983\u20131986.<ref name=\"Former Attorney General\" />\n\nMr. Bardacke attended the [[University of California at Santa Barbara]]<ref name=\"UC Santa Barbara\" /> (B.A., cum laude, 1966) and [[University of California at Berkeley]] (J.D. 1969).\n\nPaul Bardacke is an attorney who has practiced law in the public and private sectors for over 40 years.\n\nHis current practice focuses on mediation and arbitration, and Paul has mediated over 1000 cases in the past 18 years and has tried over 25 jury trials as first chair, primarily in the areas of commercial, natural resources and environmental law.\n\nHe is a founding member of the bipartisan think tank Think New Mexico.<ref>{{cite web|title=Board|url=http://www.thinknewmexico.org/board.html|publisher=Think New Mexico|accessdate=10 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nPaul also served as Chairman of Governor [[Bill Richardson]]'s successful gubernatorial campaigns in 2002.<ref name=\"Paul G. Bardacke\">{{cite web|title=Paul G. Bardacke|url=http://www.sutinfirm.com/lawyer.asp?pgb|publisher=Sutin, Thayer & Browne, APC|accessdate=10 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, he served as a member of a small US delegation to North Korea to negotiate civil rights issues.<ref>{{cite news|last=Linthicum|first=Leslie|title=Seven Days on a Voyage with Gov. Richardson|url=http://www.abqjournal.com/news/state/401366nm10-23-05.htm|accessdate=10 May 2011|newspaper=Albuquerque Journal|date=2005-10-23}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010 he was appointed by Interior Secretary [[Ken Salazar]] to the National Park Service Advisory Board for a three-year term.<ref>http://www.nps.gov/policy/advisory/members.pdf</ref>\n\nBardacke has been the recipient of the Reginald Heber Smith Fellowship (1969\u20131970), an instructor in Evidence and Trial Practice at the University of New Mexico Law School, (1973\u20131982), adjunct faculty member of the National Institute of Trial Advocacy (1978\u2014   ), Attorney General of the State of New Mexico (1983\u20131986), Special U.S. Attorney for District of New Mexico (1984\u20131985) and Special Counsel to State of New Mexico on Windfall Profits Tax Litigation (1981\u20131985) <ref name=\"Paul G. Bardacke\"/>\n\n==References==\n<ref name=\"Former Attorney General\">[http://www.thinknewmexico.org/board.html \"Think New Mexico's Board\"]</ref>\n<ref name=\"UC Santa Barbara\">[http://www.lawyers.com/New-Mexico/Albuquerque/Paul-Bardacke-1134905-a.html \"Paul Bardacke lawyer profile on Lawyers.com\"]</ref>\n<references/>\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off|us}}\n{{succession box |\n  before= [[Jeff Bingaman]] |\n  title= [[Attorney General of New Mexico]]|\n  years= 1983-1986|\n  after= [[Hal Stratton]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bardacke, Paul}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of California, Santa Barbara alumni]]\n[[Category:UC Berkeley School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:New Mexico Democrats]]\n[[Category:New Mexico Attorneys General]]\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n\n\n{{NewMexico-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Blacklisted-links|1=\n*http://www.lawyers.com/New-Mexico/Albuquerque/Paul-Bardacke-1134905-a.html\n*:''Triggered by <code>\\blawyers\\.com\\b</code> on the local blacklist''|bot=Cyberbot II|invisible=false}}\n{{BLP sources|date=December 2010}}\n'''Paul Gregory Bardacke''' (born December 16, 1944)<ref>[http://www.google.com/search?sourceid=chrome&ie=UTF-8&q=new+hampshire+birth+index+online#sclient=psy&hl=en&tbs=bks:1&q=General+corporate.+Home:+2223+E+Day+Island+Blvd+W+Tacoma+WA+98466-+1816+Office%3A+4303+N+Ruston+Way+Tacoma+WA+98402-5313+BARDACKE%2C+PAUL+GREGORY%2C+lawyer%2C+former+attorney+general%3B+b.+Oakland.+Calif.%2C+Dec.+16.+1944&aq=f&aqi=&aql=&oq=&psj=1&fp=cc7216a82c53364]</ref>     is the former [[Attorney General of New Mexico]], having served from 1983-1986.<ref name=\"Former Attorney General\" />\n\nMr. Bardacke attended the [[University of California at Santa Barbara]]<ref name=\"UC Santa Barbara\" /> (B.A., cum laude, 1966) and [[University of California at Berkeley]] (J.D. 1969).\n\nPaul Bardacke is an attorney who has practiced law in the public and private sectors for over 40 years.\n\nHis current practice focuses on mediation and arbitration, and Paul has mediated over 1000 cases in the past 18 years and has tried over 25 jury trials as first chair, primarily in the areas of commercial, natural resources and environmental law.\n\nHe is a founding member of the bipartisan think tank Think New Mexico.<ref>{{cite web|title=Board|url=http://www.thinknewmexico.org/board.html|publisher=Think New Mexico|accessdate=10 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nPaul also served as Chairman of Governor [[Bill Richardson]]'s successful gubernatorial campaigns in 2002.<ref name=\"Paul G. Bardacke\">{{cite web|title=Paul G. Bardacke|url=http://www.sutinfirm.com/lawyer.asp?pgb|publisher=Sutin, Thayer & Browne, APC|accessdate=10 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, he served as a member of a small US delegation to North Korea to negotiate civil rights issues.<ref>{{cite news|last=Linthicum|first=Leslie|title=Seven Days on a Voyage with Gov. Richardson|url=http://www.abqjournal.com/news/state/401366nm10-23-05.htm|accessdate=10 May 2011|newspaper=Albuquerque Journal|date=2005-10-23}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010 he was appointed by Interior Secretary [[Ken Salazar]] to the National Park Service Advisory Board for a three year term.<ref>http://www.nps.gov/policy/advisory/members.pdf</ref>\n\nBardacke has been the recipient of the Reginald Heber Smith Fellowship (1969\u20131970), an instructor in Evidence and Trial Practice at the University of New Mexico Law School, (1973\u20131982), adjunct faculty member of the National Institute of Trial Advocacy (1978\u2014   ), Attorney General of the State of New Mexico (1983\u20131986), Special U.S. Attorney for District of New Mexico (1984\u20131985) and Special Counsel to State of New Mexico on Windfall Profits Tax Litigation (1981\u20131985) <ref name=\"Paul G. Bardacke\"/>\n\n==References==\n<ref name=\"Former Attorney General\">[http://www.thinknewmexico.org/board.html \"Think New Mexico's Board\"]</ref>\n<ref name=\"UC Santa Barbara\">[http://www.lawyers.com/New-Mexico/Albuquerque/Paul-Bardacke-1134905-a.html \"Paul Bardacke lawyer profile on Lawyers.com\"]</ref>\n<references/>\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off|us}}\n{{succession box |\n  before= [[Jeff Bingaman]] |\n  title= [[Attorney General of New Mexico]]|\n  years= 1983-1986|\n  after= [[Hal Stratton]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bardacke, Paul}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of California, Santa Barbara alumni]]\n[[Category:UC Berkeley School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:New Mexico Democrats]]\n[[Category:New Mexico Attorneys General]]\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n\n\n{{NewMexico-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: three year \u2192 three-year, 1983-1986 \u2192 1983\u20131986", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Bardacke"}
{"title_page": "Cartoon Network (Indian TV channel)", "text_new": "{{About|a television channel available in India.|the Hindi language television channel available in the Middle East and North Africa|Cartoon Network Hindi}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox television channel\n| name = Cartoon Network\n| logofile = File:Cartoon Network logo.svg\n| logosize = \n| logocaption = \n| launch = {{Launch date and age|1995|5|1|df=y}}<br>{{Launch date and age|2018|4|15|df=y}} (HD+ channel)\n| network = Warner Bros. Global Kids & Young Adults\n| owner = [[WarnerMedia Entertainment|WarnerMedia Entertainment Networks Asia Pacific]]<ref name=Acqc>{{cite web|url=https://www.exchange4media.com/media-tv-news/pogo-cartoon-network-go-local-with-india-originals-103113.html|title=Pogo & Cartoon Network go local with India Originals - Exchange4media|website=Indian Advertising Media & Marketing News \u2013 exchange4media}}</ref>\n| picture format = 4:3 ([[576i]],[[SDTV]]),16:9 ([[1080i]], [[HDTV]])\n| country = [[India]]\n| language = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]<br/>[[Tamil language|Tamil]]<br/>[[Telugu language|Telugu]]<br/>[[English language|English]] \n| broadcast area = [[India]]<br>[[Nepal]]\n| headquarters =[[Mumbai]], India \n| sister names = [[Pogo (TV channel)|Pogo]]<br/>[[HBO India|HBO]]<br/>[[CNN International]]<br/>[[WB Channel|WB]]\n| web = [http://www.cartoonnetworkindia.com Official website]\n| sat serv 1 = [[Dish TV]]\n| sat chan 1 = Channel 953\n| sat serv 2 = [[Reliance Digital TV]]\n| sat chan 2 = Channel 605\n| sat serv 3 = [[Sun Direct]] \n| sat chan 3 = Channel 528 (SD)<br>Channel 969 (HD)\n| sat serv 4 = [[Tata Sky]]\n| sat chan 4 = Channel 666 (SD)<br>Channel 665 (HD)\n| sat serv 5 = [[Videocon d2h]]\n| sat chan 5 = Channel 501\n| sat serv 6 = [[Airtel digital TV]]\n| sat chan 6 = Channel 449 (SD)\n| sat serv 7 = [[Dish Home]] (Nepal) \n| sat chan 7 = Channel 800 (in English)\n| sat serv 8 = [[Dish TV Sri Lanka]]\n| sat chan 8 = Channel 2706\n| sat serv 9 = [[Dialog TV]] (Sri Lanka HD+ version in sd)\n| sat chan 9 = Channel 51\n| sat serv 10 = [[beIN]] (Middle East and North Africa)\n| sat chan 10 = Channel 108 (HD)\n| cable serv 1 = [[Asianet Digital]]\n| cable chan 1 = Channel 330 \n| cable serv 2 = [[Siti Cable]]\n| cable chan 2 = Channel 442 \n| cable serv 3 = [[Hathway]]\n| cable chan 3 = Channel 403 \n| cable serv 4 = In Digital\n| cable chan 4 = Channel 325\n| cable serv 5 = [[Sreedevi Digital]]\n| cable chan 5 = Channel 343\n| cable serv 6 = [[DEN Networks|DEN]]\n| cable chan 6 = Channel 429|cable serv 7=GTPL|cable chan 7=Channel 363 (SD)<br> Channel 172 (HD)}}\n\n'''Cartoon Network''' is an [[India]]n [[television channel]], operated by [[Turner International India]], available on major Indian [[Satellite television|satellite]] and [[cable television]] providers. The channel primarily airs [[animated]] shows. It is based in [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]]. It started airing on 1 May 1995 as the first kids' channel in [[India]]. It is also the sister channel of [[Pogo TV]].\n\n==History==\n===Launch===\n[[File:Cartoon Network logo 1992.svg|thumb|left|The original Cartoon Network logo, used from 1 May 1995 to 2 October 2005. The logo is still in use as a trademark.]]\nThe channel first broadcast on 1 May 1995 as a dual-channel with Cartoon Network operating from 5:30&nbsp;a.m. to 5:30&nbsp;p.m. (later 9:00&nbsp;p.m.) and [[Turner Classic Movies]] (formerly [[Turner Network Television|TNT]]) taking up the remainder of the daily schedule. On 1 July 2001, Cartoon Network (India) became a separate 24-hour channel.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k1/mar/mar23.htm|title=Cartoon Network to go 24 hours from 1 July|date=March 20, 2001|accessdate=August 10, 2017}}</ref>\nIn 2004, a [[Cartoon Network (Pakistan)|separate feed]] of the channel dedicated to Pakistani and Bangladeshi viewers was started. Programmes broadcast on this feed are different from the Indian feed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defence.pk/forums/strategic-geopolitical-issues/487-pakistan-s-very-own-cartoon-network.html |title=Pakistans very own Cartoon Network |publisher=Defence.pk |accessdate=2014-04-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111001010603/http://www.defence.pk/forums/strategic-geopolitical-issues/487-pakistan-s-very-own-cartoon-network.html |archivedate=2011-10-01 }}</ref>\n\n===1990s===\nIt originally aired only [[List of works produced by Hanna-Barbera|Hanna-Barbera cartoons]] such as ''[[The Yogi Bear Show]]'', ''[[Top Cat]]'', ''[[The Flintstones]]'', and ''[[Scooby-Doo]]''. The channel quickly started to develop, airing for the first time MGM cartoons (''[[Tom and Jerry]]'', ''[[Droopy]]'', and ''[[Spike and Tyke]]'') in 1996, and (after [[Time Warner]]'s purchase of Turner in 1996) Warner Bros shows (''[[Looney Tunes]]'', and several other Looney Tunes related cartoons) in 1997. In 1998, Cartoon Network started to air its first original shows ''[[Space Ghost Coast to Coast]]'' and ''[[The Moxy Show]]''.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nOn January 4, 1999, the channel started to offer Hindi-dubbed versions of its shows, such as ''[[Scooby-Doo, Where Are You!]]'', ''[[The Flintstones]]'', ''[[The Jetsons]]'', ''[[SWAT Kats: The Radical Squadron]]'', ''[[The Mask: The Animated Series]]'', ''[[The Addams Family (1992 animated series)|The Addams Family]]'', ''[[The Real Adventures of Jonny Quest]]'', ''[[Captain Planet]]'' and certain other select programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/1998/98oct04/nation.htm#5|title=tribuneindia... Nation|website=www.tribuneindia.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 August 1999, the channel received a rebrand, introducing new bumpers, new shows and a new 'powerhouse' theme. The new shows for 1999 were its original shows ''[[Dexter's Laboratory]]'', ''[[Cow & Chicken]]'', ''[[I Am Weasel]]'', ''[[Ed, Edd n' Eddy]]'' and ''[[Johnny Bravo]]''. The following year, 2000, saw even more Cartoon Network originals being introduced, including ''[[The Powerpuff Girls]]'', ''[[Mike, Lu & Og]]'' and ''[[Courage the Cowardly Dog]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2000/20000123/spectrum/tv.htm|title=The Sunday Tribune - Spectrum - Television|website=www.tribuneindia.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2000/20000409/spectrum/tv.htm|title=The Sunday Tribune - Spectrum - Television|website=www.tribuneindia.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2000/20000917/spectrum/tv.htm|title=The Sunday Tribune - Spectrum - Television|website=www.tribuneindia.com}}</ref>\n\n===2000s===\nIn February 2000, the channel decided to offer Tamil dubbed versions of their content.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nIn 2001 ''[[Sheep in the Big City]]'', ''[[Time Squad]]'' and ''[[Samurai Jack]]'' were launched in India .<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2001/20010304/spectrum/tv.htm|title=The Sunday Tribune - Spectrum - Television|website=www.tribuneindia.com}}</ref> On 1 July 2001, Cartoon Network (India) became a 24-hour channel.<ref name=\"auto\"/> In 2001 ''Toonami'' block was introduced that primarily consists of Japanese anime and occasionally American action animation like ''[[Dragon Ball Z]]'', ''[[Inazuma Eleven]]'', ''[[Transformers: Robots in Disguise (2001 TV series)|Transformers: Robots in Disguise]]'' and [[Superman: The Animated Series]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.afaqs.com/news/media/43443_turner-to-launch-toonami-in-india|title=Turner to launch Toonami in India|website=afaqs!}}</ref> A ''Night Shift'' block was introduced in November 2001 to target Teens and adults. The programming include ''[[Birdman and the Galaxy Trio]]'', ''[[The Brak Show]]'', ''[[Galtar and the Golden Lance]]'', ''[[Harvey Birdman, Attorney at Law]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k1/nov/nov55.htm|title=Cartoon Network gets aggressive; pits toons against saas bahus|date=20 November 2001|website=Indian Television Dot Com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003 [[Tiny TV]] a preschool programming block was launched. This block was later shifted to sister channel [[Pogo TV]].<ref name=Tiny>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k3/jan/jan108.htm|title=Cartoon network brings Noddy to India  on Tiny TV brand|date=20 January 2003|accessdate=25 June 2017}}</ref> ''[[Pok\u00e9mon (anime)|Pok\u00e9mon]]'' series was launched in 2003 which enjoyed success in India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2003/20030525/spectrum/tv.htm|title=The Sunday Tribune - Spectrum - Television|website=www.tribuneindia.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/showcase-kids-an-obsession-with-indian-parents/articleshow/2536842.cms|title=Showcase Kids: An obsession with Indian parents|date=13 November 2007|via=The Economic Times}}</ref> The channel also started acquiring local series and films in 2003 starting with [[The Adventures of Tenali Raman]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/the-tube-gets-to-tenali/224368|title=The Tube Gets to Tenali|date=5 July 2004|accessdate=10 June 2017}}</ref> Other acquisitions include series like ''The Adventures of Chhota Birbal'', ''Akbar and Birbal'' and television films like ''Vikram and Betaal''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k6/jan/jan132.htm|title=Cartoon Network goes on a local animation acquisition spree|date=11 January 2006|website=Indian Television Dot Com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k5/june/june181.htm|title=Cartoon Network to premiere \"Vikram Betal\"|date=15 June 2005|accessdate=23 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Logo Cartoon Network 2004-2010.svg|thumb|left|Cartoon Network's second logo, used in various forms and styles from 3 October 2005 to 30 September 2011]]\nIn 2005, the bumpers were replaced with 3D animations of the 'CN (Cartoon Network) City' that all the Cartoon Network toons lived in. Show-specific bumpers were replaced with 3D animations of a well-known scene from the particular show (e.g., a ''[[Dexter's Laboratory]]'' bumper would feature Dexter's house, a ''[[The Powerpuff Girls|Powerpuff Girls]]'' bumper would feature most likely the PPG household, and so forth). The retro checkerboard logo was replaced with the new 'CN' city-style logo.\n\n\n\nIt also started the anime series ''[[Beyblade]]'' on 3 June 2005,<ref name=\"Beyblade introduced in India\">{{cite web|title=Beyblade introduced in India|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/television/broadcasting/tv-channels/kids/beyblade-to-air-on-cartoon-network-on-3-june|accessdate=15 October 2014|year=2014}}</ref> which enjoyed a No.1 or No.2 position in the kids genre, along with ''[[Pok\u00e9mon (anime)|Pok\u00e9mon]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiantelevision.com/special/y2k5/beyblade.htm|title=Beyblade 'top' favourite among kids after Pokemon|date=3 September 2005|website=Indian Television Dot Com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2005/20051016/society.htm#3|title=The Tribune, Chandigarh, India - Education Tribune|website=www.tribuneindia.com}}</ref>\n\nThe channel continued to air new episodes and seasons from ''[[Beyblade]]'' and  ''Pok\u00e9mon'', and their movies, which continued to rank No.1 and No.2 in the kids' genre.<ref name=\"Pok\u00e9mon and Beyblade continue to top Kids Genre\">{{cite web|title=Pokemon and Beyblade continue to top Kids Genre|url=http://www.indiantelevision.org.in/special/y2k5/beyblade.htm|work=indiantelevision.com|accessdate=15 October 2014|year=2014}}</ref> ''Half Ticket Express'' a preschool block was launched which aired series like ''[[Dragon Tales]]'', ''[[Franklin (TV series)|Franklin]]'' and ''[[The Koala Brothers]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/tube/y2k5/mar/martube17.htm|title=Cartoon Network presents 'Half Ticket Express'|date=22 March 2005|website=Indian Television Dot Com}}</ref> Another programming block '''Thoda Meow Thoda Bow'' featuring [[Tom And Jerry]], [[Scooby-Doo]] and  [[The Sylvester & Tweety Mysteries]] was launched on [[Children's Day (India)|Children's Day]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k5/nov/nov115.htm|title=Fanfare galore lined up for kids this Children's Day|date=11 November 2005|website=Indian Television Dot Com}}</ref>\n\nCartoon Network  launched an action series titled The [[Justirisers]] on the action block Toonami on 7 March 2007 and Singer [[Shankar Mahadevan]] sunged its Title Track in Hindi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k7/feb/feb288.htm|title=Cartoon Network to launch \"Justirisers\"|date=21 February 2007|accessdate=29 June 2017}}</ref> The Series after airing all episodes was replaced by [[Sazer X]] on July 3 2007 in which [[Shaan (singer)|Shaan]] sung the  title track.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.exchange4media.com/kids-news/shaan-sings-title-track-of-cartoon-networks-action-series-sazer-x-26705.html|title=Shaan sings title track of Cartoon Network\u2019s action series \u2018Sazer X\u2019 - Exchange4media|website=Indian Advertising Media & Marketing News \u2013 exchange4media}}</ref> ''[[Boomerang (TV network)|Boomerang]]'' programming block was launched in August 2007 which aired classic properties like Tom And Jerry, Scooby-Doo and [[Popeye]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.exchange4media.com/kids-news/cartoon-network-creates-new-programming-block-to-woo-adults-26762.html|title=Cartoon Network creates new programming block to woo adults - Exchange4media|website=Indian Advertising Media & Marketing News \u2013 exchange4media}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 October 2007, Cartoon Network started the new series ''[[Ben 10 (TV series)|Ben 10]]'',<ref name=\"Ben 10 become hit in India\">{{cite web|title=Ben 10 become hit in India|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/release/y2k8/jan/janrel59.php|work=indiantelevision.com|accessdate=15 October 2014|year=2014}}</ref> \n\nOn 11 December 2009, Cartoon Network began to air the next series in the ''[[Ben 10]] franchise'', ''[[Ben 10: Alien Force]]''.<ref name=\"Ben 10 Alien Force\">{{cite web|title=Ben 10 Alien Force|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/television/broadcasting/tv-channels/kids/cn-to-air-new-series-of-ben10-alien-force-from-11-december|accessdate=15 October 2014|year=2014}}</ref>\nIt also aired new ''Ben 10'' movies.<ref name=\"Ben 10 sequel\">{{cite web|title=Ben 10 Alien Swarm movie|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/television/broadcasting/tv-channels/kids/cartoon-network-circles-the-globe-with-ben-10-alien-swarm|accessdate=15 October 2014|year=2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Ben 10 Secret of the omnitrix movie\">{{cite web|title=Ben 10 Secret of the omnitrix movie|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/television/broadcasting/tv-channels/kids/cartoon-network-to-air-ben-10-movie-on-7-september|accessdate=15 October 2014|year=2014}}</ref>\n\n===2010s===\n[[File:Cartoon Network extended logo 2010.svg|thumb|A variation of the network's current logo which resembles its original logo, used {{as of|2011|10|1|lc=y}}.]]\n\nCartoon Network started the third series ''Ben 10 franchise'', ''[[Ben 10: Ultimate Alien]]'' on 10 October 2010.<ref name=\"Ben 10 Ultimate Alien\">{{cite web|title=Ben 10 Ultimate Alien|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/release/y2k10/oct/octrel33.php|accessdate=15 October 2014|year=2014}}</ref> Cartoon Network launched [[Roll No 21]] in November 2010, multiple season and TV movies were launched after the success of first season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/radio-and-tv/Krishna-in-a-new-avatar/article15717064.ece|title=Krishna in a new avatar|date=26 November 2010|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/tv/malaysias-animasia-signs-new-pact-with-cartoon-network/|title=Malaysia\u2019s Animasia Signs New Pact with Cartoon Network|first=Ramin|last=Zahed|date=10 December 2012}}</ref> The new ''Beyblade'' series, ''[[Beyblade: Metal Fusion]]'' began to air in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiantelevision.com/television/broadcasting/tv-channels/kids/cartoon-network-to-launch-beyblade-metal-fusion|title=Cartoon Network to launch Beyblade: Metal Fusion|date=5 April 2011|website=Indian Television Dot Com}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 October 2011, Cartoon Network introduced its new branding and logo. Designed by Brand New School, it makes heavy use of the black and white checkerboard motif, as well as CMYK color variations and patterns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.underconsideration.com/brandnew/archives/cartoon_network_enters_the_grid.php|title=Brand New: Cartoon Network Enters the Grid|last=UnderConsideration|website=www.underconsideration.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref> The slogan \"It's a Fun Thing!\" was also introduced. However unlike the [[Cartoon Network (Pakistan)|Pakistan]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://asianetpakistan.com/entertainment/17512/it%E2%80%99s-a-fun-thing-only-on-cartoon-network/|title=It\u2019s a Fun Thing! Only on Cartoon Network : AsiaNet-Pakistan|website=asianetpakistan.com|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> and [[Cartoon Network (Southeast Asia)|Asian]] feeds, ''[[The Amazing World of Gumball]]'' premiered one year later as ''Gumball Ki Atrangi Duniya''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animationxpress.com/index.php/broadcast/cartoon-network-brings-the-amazing-world-of-gumball-the-global-runaway-hit-into-india|title=Cartoon Network brings \u2018The Amazing World of Gumball\u2019 - the global runaway hit into India - AnimationXpressAnimationXpress|website=www.animationxpress.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-12-21}}</ref>\n\nCN shifted ''[[Pok\u00e9mon (anime)|Pok\u00e9mon]]'' to its sister channel [[Pogo (TV channel)|Pogo]] in 2011, having aired till the eleventh season, but later brought it back on CN in 2014, starting from the fourteenth-season episode \"[[List of Pok\u00e9mon: Black & White episodes|Pok\u00e9mon: Black and White]]\".<ref name=\"Upcoming- new content from Pokemon\">{{cite web|title=Upcoming new content from Pokemon|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/television/tv-channels/news-broadcasting/cartoon-network-brings-pokemon-latest-season-and-kid-krrish-movie-sequelthis-monsoon-140630|work=indiantelevision.com|accessdate=June 2014|year=2014}}</ref>\n\n''[[Oggy and the Cockroaches]]'' was started in India in July 2012,<ref name=\"CN Oggy\">{{cite web|title=CN Oggy|url=http://www.preservearticles.com/2012091433273/oggy-and-the-cockroaches-becoming-the-most-loved-show-in-india.html|work=preservearticles.com|accessdate=15 October 2014|year=2014}}</ref> In January 2015, Cartoon Network lost the rights of Season 1-4 to [[Nickelodeon (India)|Nickelodeon]] but later acquired the rights of season 5 in December 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiantelevision.com/specials/event-coverage/asia-tv-forum/cartoon-network-acquires-oggy-and-the-cockroaches-season-5-151202|title=Cartoon Network acquires \u2018Oggy And The Cockroaches\u2019 season 5|date=2 December 2015|website=Indian Television Dot Com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 Cartoon Network acquired the rights of [[Krrish (franchise)|Krrish franchise's]] animated film series ''Kid Krrish''. The first movie ''[[Kid Krrish]] on 2 October 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/companies/kid-krrish-to-premiere-on-oct-2/article23108525.ece|title=Kid Krrish to premiere on Oct 2|first=Our|last=Bureau|website=@businessline}}</ref> The film was followed by three additional movies ''Kid Krrish: Mission Bhutan'' (19 July 2014), ''Kid Krrish: Mystery in Mongolia'' (27 September 2014) and ''Kid Krrish: Shakalaka Africa'' (25 April 2015).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiantelevision.com/television/tv-channels/news-broadcasting/cartoon-network-brings-pokemon-latest-season-and-kid-krrish-movie-sequelthis-monsoon-140630|title=Cartoon Network brings Pokemon latest season and Kid Krrish movie sequelthis monsoon|date=30 June 2014|website=Indian Television Dot Com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.adgully.com/beat-the-heat-this-summer-with-brand-new-shows-on-cartoon-network-61282.html|title=Beat the heat this summer with brand new shows on Cartoon Network|first=Adgully|last=Bureau|website=www.adgully.com}}</ref>\t\n\nCN started the fourth series ''Ben 10 franchise'', ''[[Ben 10: Omniverse]]'' on 26 November 2012.<ref name=\"Ben 10 Omniverse\">{{cite web|title=Ben 10 Omniverse|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k12/nov/nov196.php|accessdate=15 October 2014|year=2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 Cartoon Network launched three series in India, [[Uncle Grandpa]] and [[Beyblade: Shogun Steel]] on 26 April and [[Clarence (American TV series)|Clarence]] on 1 June.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/trade-news/hindi/Cartoon-Network-launches-new-show-Clarence/articleshow/47442464.cms|title=Cartoon Network launches new show 'Clarence' - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref>\n\nCartoon Network celebrated 20th Anniversary in November 2015. A programming block ''Happy Birthday Cartoon Network'' which aired ongoing series like ''[[Horrid Henry]]'' and ''Oggy and the Cockroaches'' as well as classic series like ''The Flintstones'', ''[[The Grim Adventures of Billy and Mandy]]'' and ''Courage the Cowardly Dog''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/television/tv-channels/kids/cartoon-network-turns-20-celebrates-with-new-shows-contest-150504|title=Cartoon Network turns 20; celebrates with new shows, contest|date=4 May 2015|website=Indian Television Dot Com}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2015 Cartoon Network aired two specials for the promotion of Hindi film ''[[Dilwale (2015 film)|Dilwale]]''. The first special ''Kris Aur Sharukhan Khan Ki Dilwale Bollywood Class'' aired on 19 December while ''Oggy Ki Birthday Party'' aired on 25 December.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiantelevision.com/television/tv-channels/kids/cartoon-network-pogo-go-filmy-with-shah-rukh-khan-s-dilwale-151210|title=Cartoon Network & Pogo go filmy with Shah Rukh Khan\u2019s \u2018Dilwale\u2019|date=10 December 2015|website=Indian Television Dot Com}}</ref>\n\nThe [[The Powerpuff Girls (2016 TV series)|The Powerpuff Girls reboot]] series premiered on 9 April 2016 in India and other Asian Pacific countries while the [[Ben 10 (2016 TV series)|Ben 10 reboot]] premiered on 8 October 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/television/international-shows/story/the-powerpuff-girls-to-air-in-india-from-april-9-312771-2016-03-11|title=Animation series The Powerpuff Girls returns to Indian TV after 11 years|first1=Indo-Asian News Service|last1=March 11|first2=2016UPDATED:|last2=March 11|first3=2016 10:39|last3=Ist|website=India Today}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uNPL_5zy0RU |title=Ben 10 - All-New Series (Sundays at 10:00am) (Hindi) |publisher=YouTube |date=2016-10-17 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n===2020s===\nIn March 2020 WarnerMedia Entertainment Networks Asia Pacific announced revamping of Cartoon Network by adding more local productions starting with acquisition of [[Bandbudh Aur Budbak]].<ref name=Acqc/>\n\n== Related channels ==\n=== Cartoon Network HD+ ===\n[[File:Cartoon-Network-HD-cover.jpg|thumb|Cartoon Network HD+'s Logo, Since April 15, 2018]]\n\nCartoon Network HD+ (called CN HD+ in commercials) launched on April 15, 2018. The channel was launched in India and was eventually launched on popular operators in neighbouring countries.\n\nThe channel contains shows from [[Cartoon Network Studios]] and select acquired content. Many Cartoon Network originals are shown exclusively on this channel and not available on the SD channel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiantelevision.com/television/tv-channels/kids/cartoon-network-hd-adds-tamil-telugu-feeds-180417|title=Cartoon Network HD+ adds Tamil, Telugu feeds|date=17 April 2018|website=Indian Television Dot Com}}</ref>\n\nThis channel is now available with Hindi Feed.\n----Note : Some shows and episodes are in English Feed also.\n----\n\n\nCurrent Shows ------\n\n\nBen 10 (2016)\n\nPowerpuff girls (2016)\n\nWe Bare Bears\n\nTeen Titans Go!\n\n\n\n\n\ufffc\n\n===Cartoon Network Block===\n[[Zee TV]] launched a Cartoon Network programming block in 2002. The block featured programs like [[Scooby-Doo]], [[The Mask: Animated Series]], [[The Powerpuff Girls]], [[Dexter's Laboratory]], [[Pinky and the Brain]], [[Samurai Jack]], [[The Real Adventures of Jonny Quest]], [[The Flintstones]], [[The Jetsons]], [[Tom and Jerry Kids]], [[Superman: The Animated Series]], [[Captain Planet]], [[Ed, Edd N Eddy]], [[The Road Runner Show]], [[Courage the Cowardly Dog]], [[Sheep in the Big City]], [[Mike, Lu & Og]], [[Sylvester and Tweety Mysteries]] and [[Batman: The Animated Series]]. It aired programs twice in a day.<ref name=Cartoon>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/y2k2/aug/aug87.htm|title=Cartoon Network block replaces Nick on Zee TV|date=August 14, 2002|accessdate=September 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006 [[DD National]] introduced a Cartoon Network block named \"Cartoon Network ki Duniya\" which aired programs like [[Codename: Kids Next Door]], [[M.A.D. (Indian TV programme)|M.A.D.]] (from sister channel [[Pogo TV|Pogo)]] and [[Galli Galli Sim Sim]].<ref name=CN>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k6/july/july25.htm|title=CN gets on to DD with new branded block|date=July 4, 2006|accessdate=September 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Digital and OTT deals===\nIn 2016, Turner India signed a distribution deal with [[Viacom 18]]'s [[Over-the-top media services|OTT]] app [[Voot]]. Through this strategic tie-up Voot can stream Turner's properties from Cartoon Network and [[Pogo TV]] like [[The Powerpuff Girls]], [[Ben 10]], [[Dexter's Laboratory]], [[Roll No 21|Roll No. 21]], [[Samurai Jack]], [[Johnny Bravo]] and [[M.A.D. (Indian TV programme)|M.A.D]] in their Kids section.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afaqs.com/news/story/48323_Viacom18s-Voot-and-Turner-India-strike-strategic-tie-up|title=Viacom18's Voot and Turner India strike strategic tie-up|date=June 24, 2016|accessdate=December 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, [[Turner International India]] signed a deal with [[Amazon Video|Amazon Prime Video India]]. Through this deal Amazon can stream Cartoon Network shows like [[Ben 10 (2005 TV series)]], [[Ben 10: Alien Force]], [[Ben 10: Ultimate Alien]], [[Ben 10: Omniverse]], [[Johnny Bravo]], [[The Powerpuff Girls]], [[Kumbh Karan]], [[Roll No 21]] and [[Dexter's Laboratory]] in their ''Kids and Family'' section.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://gadgets.ndtv.com/entertainment/news/amazon-prime-video-partners-turner-india-to-stream-cartoon-network-shows-1743459|title=Amazon Prime Video Partners Turner India to Stream Cartoon Network Shows|accessdate=August 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Cartoon Network Hindi ===\n{{Main|Cartoon Network Hindi}}\n[[File:Logo of Cartoon Network Hindi.png|thumb|Cartoon Network Hindi's logo, used since 1 April 2016.]]\nCartoon Network Hindi is a Hindi language television channel available in the Middle East and North Africa, aimed at Indian expatriates in the region. This version is operated by [[Turner Broadcasting System Europe|TBS Europe]] (which also handles the channels in the region), unlike the South Asian version which is a part of [[Turner Broadcasting System Asia Pacific|TBS Asia Pacific]]. Launched on 1 April 2016, the channel is exclusively available on [[BeIN Network]] satellite television platform.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://beinmediagroup.com/article/amazed-nine-new-channels-launched-bein/ | publisher=[[beIN Media Group]] | title=Be Amazed With Nine New Channels Launched By beIN |date=2016-03-31 |accessdate=2016-04-10 }}</ref>\n\n\n\n===CN+===\nIn 2014, Cartoon Network partnered with [[Tata Sky]] to launch an active service called ''CN+''. The service is available every day for about one to two hours. It airs select episodes from hit programmes such as [[Ben 10 (TV series)|Ben 10]] (and related series), [[Beyblade: Metal Fusion]] (and related series), Cartoon Network Original Shows like [[The Amazing World of Gumball]], [[League of Super Evil]], [[Tom and Jerry]] (and related series), [[Ed, Edd 'n' Eddy]], and movies from [[Ben 10]], [[Pok\u00e9mon (anime)|Pok\u00e9mon]] among others.<ref name=\"CN+\">{{cite web|title=CN+|url=http://www.tatasky.com/wps/portal/TataSky/valueaddedservices/actveservices/actvefunlearn/|work=tatasky.com|accessdate=15 October 2014|year=2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007172800/http://www.tatasky.com/wps/portal/TataSky/valueaddedservices/actveservices/actvefunlearn/|archivedate=7 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Toonami===\n{{Main|Toonami (India)}}\n\nOn February 26, 2015, Turner India launched a new channel based on its former block, [[Toonami (India)|Toonami]]. It featured shows such as ''Batman'', ''Superman'', ''Justice League'', ''Transformers'', and ''Dragon Ball Z''.<ref name=\"CN India Sister Channel launch\">{{cite web|title=CN India Sister Channel launch|url=http://www.animationxpress.com/index.php/latest-news/turner-launches-toonami-in-india-as-action-adventure-channel|work=animationxpress.com|year=2015}}</ref> On July 1, the channel transformed into a replica of Boomerang and aired shows such as ''[[The Jetsons]]'', ''[[The Flintstones]]'' and ''[[Yogi Bear]]''. The channel ceased operations at the end of May 15, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiantelevision.com/television/tv-channels/kids/is-it-the-end-of-the-road-for-anime-in-india-180510|title=Is it the end of the road for anime in India?|date=10 May 2018|website=Indian Television Dot Com}}</ref>\n\n==Programming==\n{{Main|List of programmes broadcast by Cartoon Network (India)}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Pogo (TV channel)]]\n* [[Toonami (India)]]\n* [[Cartoon Network (Pakistan)]]\n* [[List of Indian animated television series]]\n* [[List of international Cartoon Network channels ]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.cartoonnetworkindia.com/ Cartoon Network India official website]\n\n{{Cartoon Network}}\n{{Warner Bros.}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cartoon Network India}}\n[[Category:Cartoon Network India| ]]\n[[Category:Children's television channels in India]]\n[[Category:English-language television stations in India]]\n[[Category:Television stations in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 1995]]\n[[Category:1995 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Turner Broadcasting System Arabic]]\n[[Category:Indian animation]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language television channels in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|a television channel available in India.|the Hindi language television channel available in the Middle East and North Africa|Cartoon Network Hindi}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox television channel\n| name = Cartoon Network\n| logofile = File:Cartoon Network logo.svg\n| logosize = \n| logocaption = \n| launch = {{Launch date and age|1995|5|1|df=y}}<br>{{Launch date and age|2018|4|15|df=y}} (HD+ channel)\n| network = Warner Bros. Global Kids & Young Adults\n| owner = [[WarnerMedia Entertainment|WarnerMedia Entertainment Networks Asia Pacific]]<ref name=Acqc>{{cite web|url=https://www.exchange4media.com/media-tv-news/pogo-cartoon-network-go-local-with-india-originals-103113.html|title=Pogo & Cartoon Network go local with India Originals - Exchange4media|website=Indian Advertising Media & Marketing News \u2013 exchange4media}}</ref>\n| picture format = 4:3 ([[576i]],[[SDTV]]),16:9 ([[1080i]], [[HDTV]])\n| country = [[India]]\n| language = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]<br/>[[Tamil language|Tamil]]<br/>[[Telugu language|Telugu]]<br/>[[English language|English]] \n| broadcast area = [[India]]<br>[[Nepal]]\n| headquarters =[[Mumbai]], India \n| sister names = [[Pogo (TV channel)|Pogo]]<br/>[[HBO India|HBO]]<br/>[[CNN International]]<br/>[[WB Channel|WB]]\n| web = [http://www.cartoonnetworkindia.com Official website]\n| sat serv 1 = [[Dish TV]]\n| sat chan 1 = Channel 953\n| sat serv 2 = [[Reliance Digital TV]]\n| sat chan 2 = Channel 605\n| sat serv 3 = [[Sun Direct]] \n| sat chan 3 = Channel 528 (SD)<br>Channel 969 (HD)\n| sat serv 4 = [[Tata Sky]]\n| sat chan 4 = Channel 666 (SD)<br>Channel 665 (HD)\n| sat serv 5 = [[Videocon d2h]]\n| sat chan 5 = Channel 501\n| sat serv 6 = [[Airtel digital TV]]\n| sat chan 6 = Channel 449 (SD)\n| sat serv 7 = [[Dish Home]] (Nepal) \n| sat chan 7 = Channel 800 (in English)\n| sat serv 8 = [[Dish TV Sri Lanka]]\n| sat chan 8 = Channel 2706\n| sat serv 9 = [[Dialog TV]] (Sri Lanka HD+ version in sd)\n| sat chan 9 = Channel 51\n| sat serv 10 = [[beIN]] (Middle East and North Africa)\n| sat chan 10 = Channel 108 (HD)\n| cable serv 1 = [[Asianet Digital]]\n| cable chan 1 = Channel 330 \n| cable serv 2 = [[Siti Cable]]\n| cable chan 2 = Channel 442 \n| cable serv 3 = [[Hathway]]\n| cable chan 3 = Channel 403 \n| cable serv 4 = In Digital\n| cable chan 4 = Channel 325\n| cable serv 5 = [[Sreedevi Digital]]\n| cable chan 5 = Channel 343\n| cable serv 6 = [[DEN Networks|DEN]]\n| cable chan 6 = Channel 429|cable serv 7=GTPL|cable chan 7=Channel 363 (SD)<br> Channel 172 (HD)}}\n\n'''Cartoon Network''' is an [[India]]n [[television channel]], operated by [[Turner International India]], available on major Indian [[Satellite television|satellite]] and [[cable television]] providers. The channel primarily airs [[animated]] shows. It is based in [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]]. It started airing on 1 May 1995 as the first kids' channel in [[India]]. It is also the sister channel of [[Pogo TV]].\n\n==History==\n===Launch===\n[[File:Cartoon Network logo 1992.svg|thumb|left|The original Cartoon Network logo, used from 1 May 1995 to 2 October 2005. The logo is still in use as a trademark.]]\nThe channel first broadcast on 1 May 1995 as a dual-channel with Cartoon Network operating from 5:30&nbsp;a.m. to 5:30&nbsp;p.m. (later 9:00&nbsp;p.m.) and [[Turner Classic Movies]] (formerly [[Turner Network Television|TNT]]) taking up the remainder of the daily schedule. On 1 July 2001, Cartoon Network (India) became a separate 24-hour channel.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k1/mar/mar23.htm|title=Cartoon Network to go 24 hours from 1 July|date=March 20, 2001|accessdate=August 10, 2017}}</ref>\nIn 2004, a [[Cartoon Network (Pakistan)|separate feed]] of the channel dedicated to Pakistani and Bangladeshi viewers was started. Programmes broadcast on this feed are different from the Indian feed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defence.pk/forums/strategic-geopolitical-issues/487-pakistan-s-very-own-cartoon-network.html |title=Pakistans very own Cartoon Network |publisher=Defence.pk |accessdate=2014-04-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111001010603/http://www.defence.pk/forums/strategic-geopolitical-issues/487-pakistan-s-very-own-cartoon-network.html |archivedate=2011-10-01 }}</ref>\n\n===1990s===\nIt originally aired only [[List of works produced by Hanna-Barbera|Hanna-Barbera cartoons]] such as ''[[The Yogi Bear Show]]'', ''[[Top Cat]]'', ''[[The Flintstones]]'', and ''[[Scooby-Doo]]''. The channel quickly started to develop, airing for the first time MGM cartoons (''[[Tom and Jerry]]'', ''[[Droopy]]'', and ''[[Spike and Tyke]]'') in 1996, and (after [[Time Warner]]'s purchase of Turner in 1996) Warner Bros shows (''[[Looney Tunes]]'', and several other Looney Tunes related cartoons) in 1997. In 1998, Cartoon Network started to air its first original shows ''[[Space Ghost Coast to Coast]]'' and ''[[The Moxy Show]]''.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nOn January 4, 1999, the channel started to offer Hindi-dubbed versions of its shows, such as ''[[Scooby-Doo, Where Are You!]]'', ''[[The Flintstones]]'', ''[[The Jetsons]]'', ''[[SWAT Kats: The Radical Squadron]]'', ''[[The Mask: The Animated Series]]'', ''[[The Addams Family (1992 animated series)|The Addams Family]]'', ''[[The Real Adventures of Jonny Quest]]'', ''[[Captain Planet]]'' and certain other select programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/1998/98oct04/nation.htm#5|title=tribuneindia... Nation|website=www.tribuneindia.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 August 1999, the channel received a rebrand, introducing new bumpers, new shows and a new 'powerhouse' theme. The new shows for 1999 were its original shows ''[[Dexter's Laboratory]]'', ''[[Cow & Chicken]]'', ''[[I Am Weasel]]'', ''[[Ed, Edd n' Eddy]]'' and ''[[Johnny Bravo]]''. The following year, 2000, saw even more Cartoon Network originals being introduced, including ''[[The Powerpuff Girls]]'', ''[[Mike, Lu & Og]]'' and ''[[Courage the Cowardly Dog]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2000/20000123/spectrum/tv.htm|title=The Sunday Tribune - Spectrum - Television|website=www.tribuneindia.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2000/20000409/spectrum/tv.htm|title=The Sunday Tribune - Spectrum - Television|website=www.tribuneindia.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2000/20000917/spectrum/tv.htm|title=The Sunday Tribune - Spectrum - Television|website=www.tribuneindia.com}}</ref>\n\n===2000s===\nIn February 2000, the channel decided to offer Tamil dubbed versions of their content.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nIn 2001 ''[[Sheep in the Big City]]'', ''[[Time Squad]]'' and ''[[Samurai Jack]]'' were launched in India .<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2001/20010304/spectrum/tv.htm|title=The Sunday Tribune - Spectrum - Television|website=www.tribuneindia.com}}</ref> On 1 July 2001, Cartoon Network (India) became a 24-hour channel.<ref name=\"auto\"/> In 2001 ''Toonami'' block was introduced that primarily consists of Japanese anime and occasionally American action animation like ''[[Dragon Ball Z]]'', ''[[Inazuma Eleven]]'', ''[[Transformers: Robots in Disguise (2001 TV series)|Transformers: Robots in Disguise]]'' and [[Superman: The Animated Series]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.afaqs.com/news/media/43443_turner-to-launch-toonami-in-india|title=Turner to launch Toonami in India|website=afaqs!}}</ref> A ''Night Shift'' block was introduced in November 2001 to target Teens and adults. The programming include ''[[Birdman and the Galaxy Trio]]'', ''[[The Brak Show]]'', ''[[Galtar and the Golden Lance]]'', ''[[Harvey Birdman, Attorney at Law]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k1/nov/nov55.htm|title=Cartoon Network gets aggressive; pits toons against saas bahus|date=20 November 2001|website=Indian Television Dot Com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003 [[Tiny TV]] a preschool programming block was launched. This block was later shifted to sister channel [[Pogo TV]].<ref name=Tiny>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k3/jan/jan108.htm|title=Cartoon network brings Noddy to India  on Tiny TV brand|date=20 January 2003|accessdate=25 June 2017}}</ref> ''[[Pok\u00e9mon (anime)|Pok\u00e9mon]]'' series was launched in 2003 which enjoyed success in India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2003/20030525/spectrum/tv.htm|title=The Sunday Tribune - Spectrum - Television|website=www.tribuneindia.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/showcase-kids-an-obsession-with-indian-parents/articleshow/2536842.cms|title=Showcase Kids: An obsession with Indian parents|date=13 November 2007|via=The Economic Times}}</ref> The channel also started acquiring local series and films in 2003 starting with [[The Adventures of Tenali Raman]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/the-tube-gets-to-tenali/224368|title=The Tube Gets to Tenali|date=5 July 2004|accessdate=10 June 2017}}</ref> Other acquisitions include series like ''The Adventures of Chhota Birbal'', ''Akbar and Birbal'' and television films like ''Vikram and Betaal''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k6/jan/jan132.htm|title=Cartoon Network goes on a local animation acquisition spree|date=11 January 2006|website=Indian Television Dot Com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k5/june/june181.htm|title=Cartoon Network to premiere \"Vikram Betal\"|date=15 June 2005|accessdate=23 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Logo Cartoon Network 2004-2010.svg|thumb|left|Cartoon Network's second logo, used in various forms and styles from 3 October 2005 to 30 September 2011]]\nIn 2005, the bumpers were replaced with 3D animations of the 'CN (Cartoon Network) City' that all the Cartoon Network toons lived in. Show-specific bumpers were replaced with 3D animations of a well-known scene from the particular show (e.g., a ''[[Dexter's Laboratory]]'' bumper would feature Dexter's house, a ''[[The Powerpuff Girls|Powerpuff Girls]]'' bumper would feature most likely the PPG household, and so forth). The retro checkerboard logo was replaced with the new 'CN' city-style logo.\n\n\n\nIt also started the anime series ''[[Beyblade]]'' on 3 June 2005,<ref name=\"Beyblade introduced in India\">{{cite web|title=Beyblade introduced in India|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/television/broadcasting/tv-channels/kids/beyblade-to-air-on-cartoon-network-on-3-june|accessdate=15 October 2014|year=2014}}</ref> which enjoyed a No.1 or No.2 position in the kids genre, along with ''[[Pok\u00e9mon (anime)|Pok\u00e9mon]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiantelevision.com/special/y2k5/beyblade.htm|title=Beyblade 'top' favourite among kids after Pokemon|date=3 September 2005|website=Indian Television Dot Com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2005/20051016/society.htm#3|title=The Tribune, Chandigarh, India - Education Tribune|website=www.tribuneindia.com}}</ref>\n\nThe channel continued to air new episodes and seasons from ''[[Beyblade]]'' and  ''Pok\u00e9mon'', and their movies, which continued to rank No.1 and No.2 in the kids' genre.<ref name=\"Pok\u00e9mon and Beyblade continue to top Kids Genre\">{{cite web|title=Pokemon and Beyblade continue to top Kids Genre|url=http://www.indiantelevision.org.in/special/y2k5/beyblade.htm|work=indiantelevision.com|accessdate=15 October 2014|year=2014}}</ref> ''Half Ticket Express'' a preschool block was launched which aired series like ''[[Dragon Tales]]'', ''[[Franklin (TV series)|Franklin]]'' and ''[[The Koala Brothers]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/tube/y2k5/mar/martube17.htm|title=Cartoon Network presents 'Half Ticket Express'|date=22 March 2005|website=Indian Television Dot Com}}</ref> Another programming block '''Thoda Meow Thoda Bow'' featuring [[Tom And Jerry]], [[Scooby-Doo]] and  [[The Sylvester & Tweety Mysteries]] was launched on [[Children's Day (India)|Children's Day]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k5/nov/nov115.htm|title=Fanfare galore lined up for kids this Children's Day|date=11 November 2005|website=Indian Television Dot Com}}</ref>\n\nCartoon Network  launched an action series titled The [[Justirisers]] on the action block Toonami on 7 March 2007 and Singer [[Shankar Mahadevan]] sunged its Title Track in Hindi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k7/feb/feb288.htm|title=Cartoon Network to launch \"Justirisers\"|date=21 February 2007|accessdate=29 June 2017}}</ref> The Series after airing all episodes was replaced by [[Sazer X]] on July 3 2007 in which [[Shaan (singer)|Shaan]] sung the  title track.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.exchange4media.com/kids-news/shaan-sings-title-track-of-cartoon-networks-action-series-sazer-x-26705.html|title=Shaan sings title track of Cartoon Network\u2019s action series \u2018Sazer X\u2019 - Exchange4media|website=Indian Advertising Media & Marketing News \u2013 exchange4media}}</ref> ''[[Boomerang (TV network)|Boomerang]]'' programming block was launched in August 2007 which aired classic properties like Tom And Jerry, Scooby-Doo and [[Popeye]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.exchange4media.com/kids-news/cartoon-network-creates-new-programming-block-to-woo-adults-26762.html|title=Cartoon Network creates new programming block to woo adults - Exchange4media|website=Indian Advertising Media & Marketing News \u2013 exchange4media}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 October 2007, Cartoon Network started the new series ''[[Ben 10 (TV series)|Ben 10]]'',<ref name=\"Ben 10 become hit in India\">{{cite web|title=Ben 10 become hit in India|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/release/y2k8/jan/janrel59.php|work=indiantelevision.com|accessdate=15 October 2014|year=2014}}</ref> \n\nOn 11 December 2009, Cartoon Network began to air the next series in the ''[[Ben 10]] franchise'', ''[[Ben 10: Alien Force]]''.<ref name=\"Ben 10 Alien Force\">{{cite web|title=Ben 10 Alien Force|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/television/broadcasting/tv-channels/kids/cn-to-air-new-series-of-ben10-alien-force-from-11-december|accessdate=15 October 2014|year=2014}}</ref>\nIt also aired new ''Ben 10'' movies.<ref name=\"Ben 10 sequel\">{{cite web|title=Ben 10 Alien Swarm movie|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/television/broadcasting/tv-channels/kids/cartoon-network-circles-the-globe-with-ben-10-alien-swarm|accessdate=15 October 2014|year=2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Ben 10 Secret of the omnitrix movie\">{{cite web|title=Ben 10 Secret of the omnitrix movie|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/television/broadcasting/tv-channels/kids/cartoon-network-to-air-ben-10-movie-on-7-september|accessdate=15 October 2014|year=2014}}</ref>\n\n===2010s===\n[[File:Cartoon Network extended logo 2010.svg|thumb|A variation of the network's current logo which resembles its original logo, used {{as of|2011|10|1|lc=y}}.]]\n\nCartoon Network started the third series ''Ben 10 franchise'', ''[[Ben 10: Ultimate Alien]]'' on 10 October 2010.<ref name=\"Ben 10 Ultimate Alien\">{{cite web|title=Ben 10 Ultimate Alien|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/release/y2k10/oct/octrel33.php|accessdate=15 October 2014|year=2014}}</ref> Cartoon Network launched [[Roll No 21]] in November 2010, multiple season and TV movies were launched after the success of first season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/radio-and-tv/Krishna-in-a-new-avatar/article15717064.ece|title=Krishna in a new avatar|date=26 November 2010|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/tv/malaysias-animasia-signs-new-pact-with-cartoon-network/|title=Malaysia\u2019s Animasia Signs New Pact with Cartoon Network|first=Ramin|last=Zahed|date=10 December 2012}}</ref> The new ''Beyblade'' series, ''[[Beyblade: Metal Fusion]]'' began to air in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiantelevision.com/television/broadcasting/tv-channels/kids/cartoon-network-to-launch-beyblade-metal-fusion|title=Cartoon Network to launch Beyblade: Metal Fusion|date=5 April 2011|website=Indian Television Dot Com}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 October 2011, Cartoon Network introduced its new branding and logo. Designed by Brand New School, it makes heavy use of the black and white checkerboard motif, as well as CMYK color variations and patterns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.underconsideration.com/brandnew/archives/cartoon_network_enters_the_grid.php|title=Brand New: Cartoon Network Enters the Grid|last=UnderConsideration|website=www.underconsideration.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref> The slogan \"It's a Fun Thing!\" was also introduced. However unlike the [[Cartoon Network (Pakistan)|Pakistan]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://asianetpakistan.com/entertainment/17512/it%E2%80%99s-a-fun-thing-only-on-cartoon-network/|title=It\u2019s a Fun Thing! Only on Cartoon Network : AsiaNet-Pakistan|website=asianetpakistan.com|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> and [[Cartoon Network (Southeast Asia)|Asian]] feeds, ''[[The Amazing World of Gumball]]'' premiered one year later as ''Gumball Ki Atrangi Duniya''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animationxpress.com/index.php/broadcast/cartoon-network-brings-the-amazing-world-of-gumball-the-global-runaway-hit-into-india|title=Cartoon Network brings \u2018The Amazing World of Gumball\u2019 - the global runaway hit into India - AnimationXpressAnimationXpress|website=www.animationxpress.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-12-21}}</ref>\n\nCN shifted ''[[Pok\u00e9mon (anime)|Pok\u00e9mon]]'' to its sister channel [[Pogo (TV channel)|Pogo]] in 2011, having aired till the eleventh season, but later brought it back on CN in 2014, starting from the fourteenth-season episode \"[[List of Pok\u00e9mon: Black & White episodes|Pok\u00e9mon: Black and White]]\".<ref name=\"Upcoming- new content from Pokemon\">{{cite web|title=Upcoming new content from Pokemon|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/television/tv-channels/news-broadcasting/cartoon-network-brings-pokemon-latest-season-and-kid-krrish-movie-sequelthis-monsoon-140630|work=indiantelevision.com|accessdate=June 2014|year=2014}}</ref>\n\n''[[Oggy and the Cockroaches]]'' was started in India in July 2012,<ref name=\"CN Oggy\">{{cite web|title=CN Oggy|url=http://www.preservearticles.com/2012091433273/oggy-and-the-cockroaches-becoming-the-most-loved-show-in-india.html|work=preservearticles.com|accessdate=15 October 2014|year=2014}}</ref> In January 2015, Cartoon Network lost the rights of Season 1-4 to [[Nickelodeon (India)|Nickelodeon]] but later acquired the rights of season 5 in December 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiantelevision.com/specials/event-coverage/asia-tv-forum/cartoon-network-acquires-oggy-and-the-cockroaches-season-5-151202|title=Cartoon Network acquires \u2018Oggy And The Cockroaches\u2019 season 5|date=2 December 2015|website=Indian Television Dot Com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 Cartoon Network acquired the rights of [[Krrish (franchise)|Krrish franchise's]] animated film series ''Kid Krrish''. The first movie ''[[Kid Krrish]] on 2 October 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/companies/kid-krrish-to-premiere-on-oct-2/article23108525.ece|title=Kid Krrish to premiere on Oct 2|first=Our|last=Bureau|website=@businessline}}</ref> The film was followed by three additional movies ''Kid Krrish: Mission Bhutan'' (19 July 2014), ''Kid Krrish: Mystery in Mongolia'' (27 September 2014) and ''Kid Krrish: Shakalaka Africa'' (25 April 2015).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiantelevision.com/television/tv-channels/news-broadcasting/cartoon-network-brings-pokemon-latest-season-and-kid-krrish-movie-sequelthis-monsoon-140630|title=Cartoon Network brings Pokemon latest season and Kid Krrish movie sequelthis monsoon|date=30 June 2014|website=Indian Television Dot Com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.adgully.com/beat-the-heat-this-summer-with-brand-new-shows-on-cartoon-network-61282.html|title=Beat the heat this summer with brand new shows on Cartoon Network|first=Adgully|last=Bureau|website=www.adgully.com}}</ref>\t\n\nCN started the fourth series ''Ben 10 franchise'', ''[[Ben 10: Omniverse]]'' on 26 November 2012.<ref name=\"Ben 10 Omniverse\">{{cite web|title=Ben 10 Omniverse|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k12/nov/nov196.php|accessdate=15 October 2014|year=2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 Cartoon Network launched three series in India, [[Uncle Grandpa]] and [[Beyblade: Shogun Steel]] on 26 April and [[Clarence (American TV series)|Clarence]] on 1 June.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/trade-news/hindi/Cartoon-Network-launches-new-show-Clarence/articleshow/47442464.cms|title=Cartoon Network launches new show 'Clarence' - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref>\n\nCartoon Network celebrated 20th Anniversary in November 2015. A programming block ''Happy Birthday Cartoon Network'' which aired ongoing series like ''[[Horrid Henry]]'' and ''Oggy and the Cockroaches'' as well as classic series like ''The Flintstones'', ''[[The Grim Adventures of Billy and Mandy]]'' and ''Courage the Cowardly Dog''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/television/tv-channels/kids/cartoon-network-turns-20-celebrates-with-new-shows-contest-150504|title=Cartoon Network turns 20; celebrates with new shows, contest|date=4 May 2015|website=Indian Television Dot Com}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2015 Cartoon Network aired two specials for the promotion of Hindi film ''[[Dilwale (2015 film)|Dilwale]]''. The first special ''Kris Aur Sharukhan Khan Ki Dilwale Bollywood Class'' aired on 19 December while ''Oggy Ki Birthday Party'' aired on 25 December.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiantelevision.com/television/tv-channels/kids/cartoon-network-pogo-go-filmy-with-shah-rukh-khan-s-dilwale-151210|title=Cartoon Network & Pogo go filmy with Shah Rukh Khan\u2019s \u2018Dilwale\u2019|date=10 December 2015|website=Indian Television Dot Com}}</ref>\n\nThe [[The Powerpuff Girls (2016 TV series)|The Powerpuff Girls reboot]] series premiered on 9 April 2016 in India and other Asian Pacific countries while the [[Ben 10 (2016 TV series)|Ben 10 reboot]] premiered on 8 October 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/television/international-shows/story/the-powerpuff-girls-to-air-in-india-from-april-9-312771-2016-03-11|title=Animation series The Powerpuff Girls returns to Indian TV after 11 years|first1=Indo-Asian News Service|last1=March 11|first2=2016UPDATED:|last2=March 11|first3=2016 10:39|last3=Ist|website=India Today}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uNPL_5zy0RU |title=Ben 10 - All-New Series (Sundays at 10:00am) (Hindi) |publisher=YouTube |date=2016-10-17 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n===2020s===\nIn March 2020 WarnerMedia Entertainment Networks Asia Pacific announced revamping of Cartoon Network by adding more local productions starting with acquisition of [[Bandbudh Aur Budbak]].<ref name=Acqc/>\n\n== Related channels ==\n=== Cartoon Network HD+ ===\n[[File:Cartoon-Network-HD-cover.jpg|thumb|Cartoon Network HD+'s Logo, Since April 15, 2018]]\n\nCartoon Network HD+ (called CN HD+ in commercials) launched on April 15, 2018. The channel was launched in India and was eventually launched on popular operators in neighbouring countries.\n\nThe channel contains shows from [[Cartoon Network Studios]] and select acquired content. Many Cartoon Network originals are shown exclusively on this channel and not available on the SD channel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiantelevision.com/television/tv-channels/kids/cartoon-network-hd-adds-tamil-telugu-feeds-180417|title=Cartoon Network HD+ adds Tamil, Telugu feeds|date=17 April 2018|website=Indian Television Dot Com}}</ref>\n\n===Cartoon Network Block===\n[[Zee TV]] launched a Cartoon Network programming block in 2002. The block featured programs like [[Scooby-Doo]], [[The Mask: Animated Series]], [[The Powerpuff Girls]], [[Dexter's Laboratory]], [[Pinky and the Brain]], [[Samurai Jack]], [[The Real Adventures of Jonny Quest]], [[The Flintstones]], [[The Jetsons]], [[Tom and Jerry Kids]], [[Superman: The Animated Series]], [[Captain Planet]], [[Ed, Edd N Eddy]], [[The Road Runner Show]], [[Courage the Cowardly Dog]], [[Sheep in the Big City]], [[Mike, Lu & Og]], [[Sylvester and Tweety Mysteries]] and [[Batman: The Animated Series]]. It aired programs twice in a day.<ref name=Cartoon>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/y2k2/aug/aug87.htm|title=Cartoon Network block replaces Nick on Zee TV|date=August 14, 2002|accessdate=September 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006 [[DD National]] introduced a Cartoon Network block named \"Cartoon Network ki Duniya\" which aired programs like [[Codename: Kids Next Door]], [[M.A.D. (Indian TV programme)|M.A.D.]] (from sister channel [[Pogo TV|Pogo)]] and [[Galli Galli Sim Sim]].<ref name=CN>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k6/july/july25.htm|title=CN gets on to DD with new branded block|date=July 4, 2006|accessdate=September 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Digital and OTT deals===\nIn 2016, Turner India signed a distribution deal with [[Viacom 18]]'s [[Over-the-top media services|OTT]] app [[Voot]]. Through this strategic tie-up Voot can stream Turner's properties from Cartoon Network and [[Pogo TV]] like [[The Powerpuff Girls]], [[Ben 10]], [[Dexter's Laboratory]], [[Roll No 21|Roll No. 21]], [[Samurai Jack]], [[Johnny Bravo]] and [[M.A.D. (Indian TV programme)|M.A.D]] in their Kids section.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afaqs.com/news/story/48323_Viacom18s-Voot-and-Turner-India-strike-strategic-tie-up|title=Viacom18's Voot and Turner India strike strategic tie-up|date=June 24, 2016|accessdate=December 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, [[Turner International India]] signed a deal with [[Amazon Video|Amazon Prime Video India]]. Through this deal Amazon can stream Cartoon Network shows like [[Ben 10 (2005 TV series)]], [[Ben 10: Alien Force]], [[Ben 10: Ultimate Alien]], [[Ben 10: Omniverse]], [[Johnny Bravo]], [[The Powerpuff Girls]], [[Kumbh Karan]], [[Roll No 21]] and [[Dexter's Laboratory]] in their ''Kids and Family'' section.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://gadgets.ndtv.com/entertainment/news/amazon-prime-video-partners-turner-india-to-stream-cartoon-network-shows-1743459|title=Amazon Prime Video Partners Turner India to Stream Cartoon Network Shows|accessdate=August 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Cartoon Network Hindi ===\n{{Main|Cartoon Network Hindi}}\n[[File:Logo of Cartoon Network Hindi.png|thumb|Cartoon Network Hindi's logo, used since 1 April 2016.]]\nCartoon Network Hindi is a Hindi language television channel available in the Middle East and North Africa, aimed at Indian expatriates in the region. This version is operated by [[Turner Broadcasting System Europe|TBS Europe]] (which also handles the channels in the region), unlike the South Asian version which is a part of [[Turner Broadcasting System Asia Pacific|TBS Asia Pacific]]. Launched on 1 April 2016, the channel is exclusively available on [[BeIN Network]] satellite television platform.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://beinmediagroup.com/article/amazed-nine-new-channels-launched-bein/ | publisher=[[beIN Media Group]] | title=Be Amazed With Nine New Channels Launched By beIN |date=2016-03-31 |accessdate=2016-04-10 }}</ref>\n\n\n\n===CN+===\nIn 2014, Cartoon Network partnered with [[Tata Sky]] to launch an active service called ''CN+''. The service is available every day for about one to two hours. It airs select episodes from hit programmes such as [[Ben 10 (TV series)|Ben 10]] (and related series), [[Beyblade: Metal Fusion]] (and related series), Cartoon Network Original Shows like [[The Amazing World of Gumball]], [[League of Super Evil]], [[Tom and Jerry]] (and related series), [[Ed, Edd 'n' Eddy]], and movies from [[Ben 10]], [[Pok\u00e9mon (anime)|Pok\u00e9mon]] among others.<ref name=\"CN+\">{{cite web|title=CN+|url=http://www.tatasky.com/wps/portal/TataSky/valueaddedservices/actveservices/actvefunlearn/|work=tatasky.com|accessdate=15 October 2014|year=2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007172800/http://www.tatasky.com/wps/portal/TataSky/valueaddedservices/actveservices/actvefunlearn/|archivedate=7 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Toonami===\n{{Main|Toonami (India)}}\n\nOn February 26, 2015, Turner India launched a new channel based on its former block, [[Toonami (India)|Toonami]]. It featured shows such as ''Batman'', ''Superman'', ''Justice League'', ''Transformers'', and ''Dragon Ball Z''.<ref name=\"CN India Sister Channel launch\">{{cite web|title=CN India Sister Channel launch|url=http://www.animationxpress.com/index.php/latest-news/turner-launches-toonami-in-india-as-action-adventure-channel|work=animationxpress.com|year=2015}}</ref> On July 1, the channel transformed into a replica of Boomerang and aired shows such as ''[[The Jetsons]]'', ''[[The Flintstones]]'' and ''[[Yogi Bear]]''. The channel ceased operations at the end of May 15, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiantelevision.com/television/tv-channels/kids/is-it-the-end-of-the-road-for-anime-in-india-180510|title=Is it the end of the road for anime in India?|date=10 May 2018|website=Indian Television Dot Com}}</ref>\n\n==Programming==\n{{Main|List of programmes broadcast by Cartoon Network (India)}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Pogo (TV channel)]]\n* [[Toonami (India)]]\n* [[Cartoon Network (Pakistan)]]\n* [[List of Indian animated television series]]\n* [[List of international Cartoon Network channels ]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.cartoonnetworkindia.com/ Cartoon Network India official website]\n\n{{Cartoon Network}}\n{{Warner Bros.}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cartoon Network India}}\n[[Category:Cartoon Network India| ]]\n[[Category:Children's television channels in India]]\n[[Category:English-language television stations in India]]\n[[Category:Television stations in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 1995]]\n[[Category:1995 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Turner Broadcasting System Arabic]]\n[[Category:Indian animation]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language television channels in India]]\n", "name_user": "2409:4063:401e:f8e3:6d12:7307:8b37:7fc5", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(CN HD+ changes available in Hindi feed with current shows.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cartoon_Network_(Indian_TV_channel)"}
{"title_page": "Kingfisher (beer)", "text_new": "{{Primary sources|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox beverage\n| name         = Kingfisher\n| image        = Kingfisher beer logo.png\n| type         = [[Lager]]\n| abv          = 4.8%\n| proof        =\n| manufacturer = [[United Breweries Group]]\n| distributor  =\n| origin       = [[India]]\n| introduced   = 1857\n| discontinued =\n| colour       = \n| flavour      = \n| variants     = Kingfisher Premium <br /> Kingfisher Strong <br /> Kingfisher Strong Fresh <br /> Kingfisher Draught <br /> Kingfisher Ultra <br /> Kingfisher Blue<br /> Kingfisher Red <br /> Kingfisher Lager <br /> Kingfisher Storm\n| related      = {{ubl|Kingfisher Bohemia|Zingaro|UB Export|London Pilsner|Kalyani Black Label|Bullet|Peacock Cider|Bintang Beer|Pearl River Beer|}}\n| website      = {{hlist|[http://www.kingfisherworld.com Kingfisher (global)]|[http://www.kingfisherbeer.co.uk Kingfisher (Europe)]}}\n}}\n\n'''Kingfisher''' is an Indian beer brewed by [[United Breweries Group]], [[Bangalore]]. The brand was launched in  hud dabang dabang party karo yaaro 1978. With a market share of over 36% in India, it is also available in 52 other countries.<ref name=\"kingfisherworld1\">{{cite web|title=Our Brands |url=http://uat.kingfisherworld.com/corporate/ubl_brand.aspx |accessdate=20 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130712200123/http://uat.kingfisherworld.com/corporate/ubl_brand.aspx |archivedate=12 July 2013 }}</ref> The [[Heineken International|Heineken Group]] holds 42.4% equity shares in United Breweries Ltd.<ref>{{cite web |title=About Us: UBL at a glance |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/vijay-mallya-may-step-down-as-united-breweries-chairman/articleshow/52474320.cms}}</ref>\nKingfisher is ranked 74th among India's most trusted brands according to the [[The Brand Trust Report|Brand Trust Report]] 2012, a study conducted by Trust Research Advisory. In the Brand Trust Report 2013, Kingfisher was ranked 102nd among India's most trusted brands and subsequently, according to the Brand Trust Report 2014, Kingfisher was ranked 198th among India's most trusted brands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.trustadvisory.info/allindia_2014.html |title=India's Most Trusted Brands 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150502221904/http://www.trustadvisory.info/allindia_2014.html |archivedate= 2 May 2015 }}</ref>\n\nDuring the years 2009 through 2015, United Spirits (USL) / Diageo exited all non-core investments in United Breweries and sold 850,000 INR shares to Heineken, which will now give it leverage to managing affairs of India's largest beer producer. USL sold 3.21% shares for Rs 872 crore in a block trade. The shares were sold at Rs 1,030 apiece, a slight premium to Tuesday's closing price of Rs 1,014.10. As of July 2015, Heineken's stake in United Breweries (UB) has increased from 39% to 42.1%. This deal will give Heineken an upper hand over Vijay Mallya in running the company.\n\n'''Kingfisher Beer Europe Ltd. (KBE)''' is the European arm of [[United Breweries Group|United Breweries]] with a head office in Maidstone, Kent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kingfisherbeer.co.uk/|title=Kingfisher Beer UK|website=www.kingfisherbeer.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2017-03-29}}</ref> In the UK, Kingfisher is brewed under licence by Heineken but to the same recipe as used in India. The company runs independently of Kingfisher World and has its own assets such as website, social media, POS suite & marketing objectives such as the tagline, 'The Real Taste of India' which highlights the brand's genuine heritage and sets it apart from other similar products in the UK & Europe.\n\nKBE sell only one Kingfisher variant; Kingfisher Premium, which is available in four formats; 330ml (24 x 330ml cases), 650ml (12 x 650ml case), pint or half pint draught and kegs (30 or 50L).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kingfisherbeer.co.uk/trade|title=Kingfisher Beer UK|website=kingfisherbeer.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2017-03-29}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, KBE launched <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.foodbev.com/news/indian-beer-brand-kingfisher-eyes-untapped-opportunity-with-new-cider/|title=Indian beer brand Kingfisher eyes 'untapped' opportunity in cider - FoodBev Media|website=www.foodbev.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-03-29}}</ref> Peacock Cider: a 'quality apple cider' created to 'elegantly complement Asian flavours, providing a burst of apple refreshment to balance aromatic spices.'<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.instagram.com/PeacockCider|title=Peacock Cider (@peacockcider) \u2022 Instagram photos and videos|website=www.instagram.com|language=en|access-date=2017-03-29}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, KBE added two more products to its portfolio - [[Bintang Beer]], 'Indonesia's No.1 Beer' and Pearl River Beer, an 'Iconic Cantonese Beer'.\n\n==See also==\n* {{portal-inline|Beer}}\n*[[Kingfisher Airlines]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Kingfisher (beer)}}\n* {{official website|url=https://www.kingfisherworld.com/}} Global\n* {{official website|url=http://www.kingfisherbeer.co.uk}} Europe\n* {{twitter|id=KingfisherBeer}}\n* {{facebook|id=kingfisherworld}}\n\n{{United Spirits}}\n\n[[Category:Indian beer brands]]\n[[Category:Indian brands]]\n[[Category:Products introduced in 1978]]\n[[Category:United Spirits brands]]\n", "text_old": "{{Primary sources|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox beverage\n| name         = Kingfisher\n| image        = Kingfisher beer logo.png\n| type         = [[Lager]]\n| abv          = 4.8%\n| proof        =\n| manufacturer = [[United Breweries Group]]\n| distributor  =\n| origin       = [[India]]\n| introduced   = 1857\n| discontinued =\n| colour       = \n| flavour      = \n| variants     = Kingfisher Premium <br /> Kingfisher Strong <br /> Kingfisher Strong Fresh <br /> Kingfisher Draught <br /> Kingfisher Ultra <br /> Kingfisher Blue<br /> Kingfisher Red <br /> Kingfisher Lager <br /> Kingfisher Storm\n| related      = {{ubl|Kingfisher Bohemia|Zingaro|UB Export|London Pilsner|Kalyani Black Label|Bullet|Peacock Cider|Bintang Beer|Pearl River Beer|}}\n| website      = {{hlist|[http://www.kingfisherworld.com Kingfisher (global)]|[http://www.kingfisherbeer.co.uk Kingfisher (Europe)]}}\n}}\n\n'''Kingfisher''' is an Indian beer brewed by [[United Breweries Group]], [[Bangalore]]. The brand was launched in 1978. With a market share of over 36% in India, it is also available in 52 other countries.<ref name=\"kingfisherworld1\">{{cite web|title=Our Brands |url=http://uat.kingfisherworld.com/corporate/ubl_brand.aspx |accessdate=20 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130712200123/http://uat.kingfisherworld.com/corporate/ubl_brand.aspx |archivedate=12 July 2013 }}</ref> The [[Heineken International|Heineken Group]] holds 42.4% equity shares in United Breweries Ltd.<ref>{{cite web |title=About Us: UBL at a glance |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/vijay-mallya-may-step-down-as-united-breweries-chairman/articleshow/52474320.cms}}</ref>\nKingfisher is ranked 74th among India's most trusted brands according to the [[The Brand Trust Report|Brand Trust Report]] 2012, a study conducted by Trust Research Advisory. In the Brand Trust Report 2013, Kingfisher was ranked 102nd among India's most trusted brands and subsequently, according to the Brand Trust Report 2014, Kingfisher was ranked 198th among India's most trusted brands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.trustadvisory.info/allindia_2014.html |title=India's Most Trusted Brands 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150502221904/http://www.trustadvisory.info/allindia_2014.html |archivedate= 2 May 2015 }}</ref>\n\nDuring the years 2009 through 2015, United Spirits (USL) / Diageo exited all non-core investments in United Breweries and sold 850,000 INR shares to Heineken, which will now give it leverage to managing affairs of India's largest beer producer. USL sold 3.21% shares for Rs 872 crore in a block trade. The shares were sold at Rs 1,030 apiece, a slight premium to Tuesday's closing price of Rs 1,014.10. As of July 2015, Heineken's stake in United Breweries (UB) has increased from 39% to 42.1%. This deal will give Heineken an upper hand over Vijay Mallya in running the company.\n\n'''Kingfisher Beer Europe Ltd. (KBE)''' is the European arm of [[United Breweries Group|United Breweries]] with a head office in Maidstone, Kent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kingfisherbeer.co.uk/|title=Kingfisher Beer UK|website=www.kingfisherbeer.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2017-03-29}}</ref> In the UK, Kingfisher is brewed under licence by Heineken but to the same recipe as used in India. The company runs independently of Kingfisher World and has its own assets such as website, social media, POS suite & marketing objectives such as the tagline, 'The Real Taste of India' which highlights the brand's genuine heritage and sets it apart from other similar products in the UK & Europe.\n\nKBE sell only one Kingfisher variant; Kingfisher Premium, which is available in four formats; 330ml (24 x 330ml cases), 650ml (12 x 650ml case), pint or half pint draught and kegs (30 or 50L).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kingfisherbeer.co.uk/trade|title=Kingfisher Beer UK|website=kingfisherbeer.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2017-03-29}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, KBE launched <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.foodbev.com/news/indian-beer-brand-kingfisher-eyes-untapped-opportunity-with-new-cider/|title=Indian beer brand Kingfisher eyes 'untapped' opportunity in cider - FoodBev Media|website=www.foodbev.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-03-29}}</ref> Peacock Cider: a 'quality apple cider' created to 'elegantly complement Asian flavours, providing a burst of apple refreshment to balance aromatic spices.'<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.instagram.com/PeacockCider|title=Peacock Cider (@peacockcider) \u2022 Instagram photos and videos|website=www.instagram.com|language=en|access-date=2017-03-29}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, KBE added two more products to its portfolio - [[Bintang Beer]], 'Indonesia's No.1 Beer' and Pearl River Beer, an 'Iconic Cantonese Beer'.\n\n==See also==\n* {{portal-inline|Beer}}\n*[[Kingfisher Airlines]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Kingfisher (beer)}}\n* {{official website|url=https://www.kingfisherworld.com/}} Global\n* {{official website|url=http://www.kingfisherbeer.co.uk}} Europe\n* {{twitter|id=KingfisherBeer}}\n* {{facebook|id=kingfisherworld}}\n\n{{United Spirits}}\n\n[[Category:Indian beer brands]]\n[[Category:Indian brands]]\n[[Category:Products introduced in 1978]]\n[[Category:United Spirits brands]]\n", "name_user": "42.111.24.8", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kingfisher_(beer)"}
